categories: Breakfast & Brunch, Burgers, American (Traditional), American (New), Restaurants
text:
A local favorite with solid service that's very friendly and accommodating. And, they serve good diner food. We've been there several times for breakfast & lunch. (They're only open until 2:30 pm.) I adore their hash browns, they're crispy & cooked well. Plus, they make crispy bacon. The eggs taste buttery. 

My husband is a fan of their gravy; and, their lunch sandwiches are huge. But, if you don't have a big appetite, Farmer Boy has a menu section for "Smaller Appetites." 

There's usually a line on the weekends, but it moves fast. There's also a large counter to sit at plus a few outdoor tables. Parking can be limited. Farmer Boy has diner decor & is extremely clean. It's super loud inside & if you're with anyone who uses a hearing aid sit close to them.

name: Cloud Climbers Jeep Tours
categories: Tours, Hotels & Travel, Wine Tours
text:
Cloud Climbers was a great way to explore Santa Barbara Wine Country.  John, our driver, was fun and had great wine knowledge.  Having never been to the Ynez wine region, I appreciated that John selected 3 very different types of wine houses (small emerging, larger more established, and a large house spin off).  It was a wonderful way to see all that the region has to offer.  And John's knowledge of the area allowed him to listen to our feedback on what we liked and tailor the trip.  

Only recommendation is to bring a sweater on the trip.  The jeep is open and there are blankets, but the 40minute drive back to Santa Barbara can get cool when the sun goes behind the hills.

text:
I visited this place this morning with my 5 girlfriends. The place is lively and their menu looks delicious! 

Our brunch started off well. We ordered the cinammon beignets and fried green tomatoes for the table and they were delicious. However, after we placed our entrees the service got very sloppy and our waitress wasn't attentive at all. At one point all of us had to Wave our hands to get an attendants attention. It was annoying especially because the place wasn't even that crowded and  the waitress pretended like she was overwhelmed. 

I ordered the pumpkin oatmeal waffle and it wasn't that great either. None of my friends enjoyed theirs either. 

There was also a goof up on our check. 

The 3 stars are for our small plates order and the fact that one of the attendants ran across the street to handover our forgotten takeout order. That was very sweet.

text: Restaurant is nice. Menu is well done. But FOH staff needs some refreshers on what service is, especially for the price that one is paying. There was a couple behind me and we both noticed how no one acknowledged us for abt 10 min before they even got our name into opentable. They were having a conversation with the guest ahead of us , which was nice but at least a welcome in or nod would have sufficed . Menu was nice but food wasn't executed properly. I got the infamous queso fundido. Which really wasn't anything to rave about. And the vegetarian option , quesadillas de calabaza. To be honest with you I was excited when I read hand made tortillas , but the tortilla was super thick and doughy. It became overpowering. There was almost no sign of la flor de calabaza. The cocktails were spot on ! I would come back for the cocktails ! The server brought me my check without offering any dessert until I asked her if they had any at all ( no up-selling). I hear locals raving about this place but i wouldn't recommend if I was one .

categories: Seafood, Cajun/Creole, American (New), Restaurants
text: My friend who had gone here with his roommates would not stop talking about how great their soft shell crab was. Oh, to get off tangent but one night I had soft shell crab and broke out into hives the whole nine so after that I haven't touched soft shell crabs. But he swore up and down how delicious this restaurant was so I decided to check it out. We got in after a 20 minute wait. The service here is impeccable, our waitress was so friendly, helpful, and attentive. He ordered the Louisiana soft shell crabs (of course) and I got the crawfish etouffee. We couldn't decide if we wanted Original oysters Rockefeller or Oysters Palace but our waitress suggested we get half of each so we did. I usually like my oysters raw with a splash of lemon juice and tabasco sauce. But WOW, party in my mouth. The muffins that they serve was delicious, the jalapeno was my favorite. I'm usually a girl with a big appetite but I wasn't able to finish my crawfish etouffee. Food+atmosphere is very enjoyable.

text:
Have been coming to this location since I first started UCSB, and let me tell you... they NEVER disappoint! Just be warned, you'll probably always have to wait in the drive thru for at least 30 minutes, I recommend going inside!

I was ordering in the drive thru today & my worker was Ismael, he was super nice and friendly and gave me a recommendation to try the arnold palmer! I personally like the LemonUp more, but it was still pretty good if you like less sweet drinks! 

Let me put y'all on my order: 
- cheese fries 
- cheeseburger w/ grilled onions (sometimes 2x2)
- pink lemonup (pink lemonade & sprite)

name: Santa Barbara Museum of Art
attributes: {'GoodForKids': 'True'}
categories: Art Museums, Arts & Entertainment, Specialty Schools, Art Schools, Museums, Education
text:
-a surprising find. went in to get out of the rain, discovered the admission was free that day!
-small, very manageable gallery, but with a lot to see. 
-the art was very well described, as were the bios of the artists
-the collection and current exhibitions were quite diverse (paintings, paper, pottery, statues, and lovely Japanese screens and garments), so there was definitely something for everyone, but overall I found the modern/contemporary art underrepresented
-two very lovely monet paintings were a surprise and I loved the ivan aivazovsky russian fleet
-the front staff was really nice and cordial, but there was no staff throughout the gallery to ask questions of
-I'll definitely come back to check out the new exhibitions next time I'm in town, as they made up more than half the museum

text: Had the most wonderful evening dining at the Little Door!  Magical setting coupled with outstanding service and the most delicious food.   We didn't want to leave!  So enjoyed the owner/chef, hostess and bartender who all made us feel like we were family.  This was so much more than just another night in another restaurant.  Everyone raved about their food. name: Big Brand Tire & Service - Goleta
attributes: {'BusinessAcceptsCreditCards': 'True', 'ByAppointmentOnly': 'False', 'WiFi': "u'free'"}
categories: Automotive, Oil Change Stations, Auto Repair, Tires
text:
In fairness, this review is for an experience that took place a few years back, but I still think about it whenever I think about tires. Because I have no life and can't let anything go.

I was actually given the name of a guy who worked here from a work friend who was a friend of this guy, so I thought I was in good hands. In retrospect, he saw me coming a mile away. Unfortunately, I felt like I was over-sold some tires and at the time I was too embarrassed to speak up and say that I couldn't (or wouldn't) pay that much for  two tires. Also, despite the fact that I had two very good tires on the car, they kind of pushed me into getting four new tires instead of rotating the two. 

I paid about $200 more than I would have at Costco, which I consider a mid-range tire place in terms of cost. And yes, I mean for the same size, weight, tread and brand of tire. And yes, I mean if I'd bought four instead of two. That is a huge price difference. 

I didn't have to wait long (maybe about an hour which was the quoted time) and they were friendly. And my tires were done right, nothing was off-kilter or out of alignment. They did a good job technically. But I felt ripped off and I wouldn't go back.

text:
Found this place on yelp and wasn't disappointed even a bit! The service was amazing, the ambiance is great and food was fantastic. I can't wait to go back when it's a little warmer out and sit on the patio because it was so gorgeous! I went in for dinner on a Tuesday night and it was surprisingly busy. I definitely recommend making a reservation and be sure to specify if you want to be seated indoor or outdoors. 

I ordered the Maravillosa gin & tonic and it was so refreshing and yummy. We also got the negroni, which was just as delicious. We were all vegetarian at the table, but there were still so many options. The pintxos were cute presentation-wise. We ordered the patatas bravas, pimientos and white asparagus without the jamon serrano, and they were all so yummy! I think my favorite were the pimientos. Those were some of the most flavorful shishito peppers I'd had in a while! For the main meal we ordered 2 verduras paellas. The flavor was great and the portions were perfect. I loved the eggplant and different mushrooms they mixed in with it. Finally for dessert we ordered churros and the pan de chocolate. The churros were not as soft as I'd have liked them to be, but they were still really good. The pan de chocolate was so intensely chocolate, and I loved every bit of it.

Definitely can't wait to be back and check out more of the menu!

Long-term lovers of Corazon here. We've had great meals and pretty good meals. Today we stopped in for a late lunch. We were served by a woman working the counter solo and she was HUSTLING! 

We wanted to give a shout-out to her great service. And on top of that, the food was some of the best we've had in years from this spot! The ceviche was maybe the tiniest bit aged. But the spectacular tacos, salsa and guacamole 100% made up for it. 

Glad to see Corazon serving some of its best food yet!

name: Tilford Welding
attributes: {'BusinessAcceptsCreditCards': 'False'}
categories: Metal Fabricators, Local Services
text: What a great and effective man.  I was a stranger with a sculpture that required a skillful and artistic repair.  John had been recommended by one of his colleagues as "the most skillful welder in Santa Barbara".  I showed John the problem and he said he could fix it in a day or two.  We discussed that the repair would remove some of the patina, but that I could probably get some paint to fix it.  When I arrived to pick it up, John had not only fixed the broken legs on the eagle, he also had found some paint to visually repair the patina.  I was most grateful.  And "he did not charge me an arm and a leg" for his work, as predicted by his colleague.  I have found a skillful and trusted craftsman who has treated me as a friend.  Thank you for your skill and friendship.

I used to go here very regularly back when it was Mojo Coffee, and the vibe has definitely changed. The comfortable couches, the book exchange shelf,  the chess set and daily trivia are gone and replaced with simple tables and paintings.

And the service is friendly and awesome.

text: My husband and I come from two big Italian families, so we like to think we know our Italian! We heard about Ca'Dario from two different people, in two different conversations that said we HAD to go there when we were in town. Boy were we glad! The seafood risotto and sage ravioli were absolutely unbelievable. My sister and I split both of those dishes and were in heaven. The restaurant is small, so prepare to be sitting close to other people, but honestly I can't find one other thing to "complain" about. Definitely go if you can!

text:
Lilly's Tacos is a very casual and laid back joint close to the sea in Santa Barbara. The menu is short and to the point, which I love. The salsa bar was such a great addition and made the experience. Super delicious and fresh ingredients shine through here! The veggie tacos were really good, but nothing creative and super memorable. That's why I give four stars. I do not eat meat, so maybe my review would be different if I were able to try the chicken or beef options. 

Overall I would recommend a stop by for a snack or a quick bite when I'm the area!

text: Four of us went in just for drinks on a Friday night, and were astounded at how nice and big they've made the restaurant, and how nicely everything is laid out! Decor, layout, bar, outside patio... all of it looked great! We were enjoying ourselves so much, we decided to stay for dinner as well. The restaurant was so packed, that our server was initially overwhelmed, which could have been a bad thing, but then the manager, Brenden, came and offered to buy us a round of drinks, completely saving the day! Our server caught up, and the food was great (especially the Carnitas). Props to the manager, staff and owners for doing it right at this location!

text:
Two days ago, this was our last meal on our Santa Barbara mid-winter break family trip.  We checked out of our Airbnb and had time for lunch before we needed to head to the airport.  I had researched and bookmarked various SB restaurants pre-trio, and looking through my options for a good lunch spot, Wildwood popped up.  It is located in The Mill, a creatively repurposed circa-1904 feed mill.

We weren't super hungry, so hubs and I split 2 starters- 1/2dz smoked chicken wings ($8, natural wings tossed in wildwood wing sauce and served with cucumber and celery) and the shrimp & hushpuppies ($16, cajun blackened shrimp, vegetable chips, cornmeal fritters, roasted jalapeño remoulade, parsley).  They have an amazing kids menu, and kids 9 and under eat free with purchase of $10 spent on food (one kid plate per time per child).  So we got the pulled pork slider & fries for the little, knowing she would only eat the fries.  I had one last glass of a local SB white wine- the Brander Granache Blanc ($12).  The wings and the pulled pork slider were delicious, I honestly would have been a happy camper with only a few of those tender and flavorful pulled pork sliders and nothing else! The shrimp & hushpuppies were both on the (very) dry side, but the plate dressing was sooooo delicious with crunchy little fried veggie chips and that remoulade and pickles was tasty, tasty, tasty!

SB weather has finally warmed up (the rest of our vacation had been unseasonably cold) so we enjoyed the sun out on the back patio- which was a cute little courtyard housing the back patios of a winery's tasting room, a craft beer brewery, and the Millworks, a local boutique curating local handmade art, jewelry, home goods, and furniture.

A beautiful last memory of SB before heading back to rainy & cold Seattle!

categories: Seafood, Nightlife, Hotels, Event Planning & Services, American (New), Bars, Diners, Restaurants, Hotels & Travel, Breakfast & Brunch
text: On the first Saturday after Spring Equinox, we decided to visit the El Encanto for High Tea. Arrived late - packed 101 of course - but had called the restaurant twice from the road and there was no problem getting seated. Beautiful view, casually elegant patio/terrace, service was impeccable. We chose the Bellini version of high tea and their version of this summer aperitif did not disappoint - perfect, not too sweet. We decided on oolong tea, served in individual pots, and were quite taken aback when the tea arrived, made with teabags. Teabags at a high tea service - unheard of. I stuck it out with mine, but wifey immediately changed hers to loose leaf "Halo," upon the recommendation of the pleasant female server. The 3-tiered stand then arrived, together with a separate plate of jams, jellies and clotted cream. The little finger sandwiches were rather bland and underwhelming; salmon was farmed, cucumber sandwich was not vibrant, egg salad was without any specific flavor, topping the most boring squares of white Wonderbread imaginable - they could not even muster a pumpernickel. The scones were tiny but perfectly fine. The dessert items were very good, and made in-house. We had a very nice discussion with the manager on how to change things around for them, as the staff clearly tries hard, but their tea service is very basic - not commensurate with a hotel that holds itself out as a luxury property. For us, we would rather have paid double and had more plentiful fare, more vibrancy and flavor of the food items, and absolutely no tea bags in sight. For comparison, the Peninsula in Beverly Hills still holds top place as best tea service in SoCal.

text:
I went in on a Sunday for an Iced Latte and decided to stay and have breakfast as well.  I ordered a Breakfast burrito straight off the menu with no additions or substitutions and an iced vanilla latte and then took a seat outside.  It took about 15 min for my latte to make it out to me.  The table next to me ordered their food right before I did and they got their food, chatted, had coffee and left by the time I finally got up to find out what happened to my burrito.  When I asked the waiter where my food was he told me "3 minutes" rather than apologize for the delay or offer any kind of compensation or refund.  When my burrito finally arrived I asked why I had to wait 40 minutes for a breakfast burrito and the waiter confessed that he served my food to another table by mistake.  

I won't go back there again.  I don't think the wait and the burrito were worth the $12 they charged.  The Daily Grind has better breakfast burritos and they are half the price.

name: Santa Barbara Gas
categories: Smog Check Stations, Automotive, Gas Stations
text:
I looked online to find the best gas prices in Santa Barbara and was surprised the lowest price was a few blocks away at Santa Barbara Gas. It is a station that I pass at least 10 times a week but never noticed or gave it a thought. I drove up and saw a gentleman in a uniform hand a flower to the passenger in the car next to me. I thought it must be a friend. Like in the days of yore, this gentleman offered to help me pump my gas, then proceeded to ask me what my favorite color flower  was. He had a flower bed in the corner of the property at the gas station. I told him they were beautiful but to "let the flowers live" :-)

It has been so many years since I have seen someone actually come out from the office and offer to help except for the 76 station at Santa Monica Rd. but that's 10 Miles out of my way.

The gas was 15 cents less per gallon than my usual station. I told Ray, he just earned a new loyal customer!

text: Love this place, I think I'm here at least once a week, or twice if I get a last minute food order.  I prefer to shop here for most of my fruits and veggies, if I'm not going to make it to farmers market.  All their produce seems fresh and actually it is priced fairly, they have tons of organic items (my choice) and they don't break the bank.  And the people are always restocking making sure shelves are full and never empty.  Plus they all seem to be always super friendly and in good mood.  The bathrooms are always clean and the sample station is also always clean.  Coffee sampling place sometimes can seem a bit messy, but it just takes one person to mess that up, but did see a crew member get to it right away.  Good selection of cheeses, beer and wines.  And I do love the "what's new section" always great new finds.  So yes I will continue to shop at Trader Joe's!! Wish there was something that could be done with the parking lot,!

name: Adobe Pet Hospital

text: I'm not a big reviewer, but when I read the Anna B. review, I was shocked concerned and wondered what happened. I asked Dr. Gibbs about it, something the reviewer stated she declined wanting, and got a complete and through explanation. It is a shame that one person can damage the reputation of such a professional and caring veterinarian who is passionate about her job and especially her human clients. This is a person who calls you on her own time to check on your animals and you the they are sick. They call to make sure one of your animals that they haven't even seen is okay when hearing they were in the ER. Actually give you an opinion and options. Sit on the floor with your pets. Both doctors at Adobe are first rate. They do everything they can to care for your animals with good communication and are extremely reasonable in cost! They often even comp us items. Even the best of professionals need professional or at least reasonable clients. When they don't have them, they do the best they can at the risk of receiving a ridiculous review that cannot be verified. Any reviewer who actually states that they don't want an explanation and will not provide a platform for discussion should be severely discounted or removed from Yelp. This is dicey with healthcare providers. Please consider their livelihood based on what you say which was actually found useful by three people. Obviously humous for its gross mischaracterization. Please judge for yourself or by ALL of the off the chart reviews.

name: City of Santa Barbara
attributes: {'ByAppointmentOnly': 'False', 'GoodForKids': 'True'}
categories: Local Flavor, Public Services & Government
text:
I've driven to and through Santa Barbara more than a few times. By car, bus and now Amtrak with local buses. And I must say, if you're traveling alone public transportation does allow you to see more places, especially if you get lost easily without use of a Garmin or Google Maps. 

I probably should have planned an itinerary, especially with public transportation. I just didn't know how.... The places I haven't visited here yet; Santa Barbara Zoo and Wineries (because I live really close to LA Zoo. Also, San Diego Zoo and Napa Valley are top of my Places To Visit List).

It's a beautiful city. The beach with fog looks so yucks. I'd be scared to surf, but people do it. I saw them today. The place is  laid back, but there's plenty to do like Arts , Films & Festivals. 

***Today, I learned how to screwdriver a hot dog into a condiment-filled baguette bun, because it's the French way. What else?

***Every nickel and dime adds up quicker than pennies. Collect 10 bottles a day for $7 a week, which if saved is $364 a year... But where to recycle?

***Well, French people are smart enough to be bored and design wind chimes that can easily sell for much more than a buck in recycled bottle trash cash. Paint it, bead it... Make more money. 

***Cabbage or rich greens should be eaten everyday; boil, raw, steam, pickle or whatever because it's healthy. You don't have to like it just eat it. Some things are meant to habitual and the addiction is better than mind-altering drugs. Lolz but true. 

No celebrity sightings via public transportation. The locals are friendly for the most part. A few people just wanted to stare at my face today. Idk why.

I heart the City of Santa Barbara.

text:
Pretty good experience of authentic Thai food. Definitely a bit higher end on the presentation. The service was fast and pleasant. Definitely will go back. 

The pictures really don't do the place much justice. I walked in expecting a darker place. When in fact it's pretty vibrant and pleasant. There's this one extremely large picture of a Thai village. I could stare at the thing all day trying to decipher it. Haha. 

Orders a beef salad and had the chicken eggplant dish. Both were tasty. This place serves large dishes but definitely not a family style place as they are smaller portions than most other Thai places.   But, hey! You trade quality for quantity. Worth the trade sometimes. 

I committed the sin of not ordering Pad Thai. Blame the diet gots of spring so that I can get in shape. Definitely worth the meal. Decent price for a nicer dine-in location. Small and cute.  

Enjoy!

text:
Love this place!! 

A little hidden away from everything but still worth the trip across the Storke bridge. I think it'd do well other places in goleta/Sb as well. Maybe a 2nd location down the road?

I've enjoyed everything I've ordered here, just certain things more than others. My favorites are the brisket sirloin burger, spicy green beans, tri tip and the jalapeño poppers. I'm sure not everything, but it actually does seem like a good amount of the food is home made and done fresh. 

The staff I've dealt with have all been pleasant in each one I've been in. The owner I'm assuming is also always there which is awesome to see. He seems like a good dude and cares about serving quality food to the area and community. High influence with DPHS being around the corner. 

Overall, definitely check it out and support local businesses and eateries! One of my new favorite spots in goleta area since arriving.

text:
Well! Called Husted Plumbing for the first time for help unclogging a toilet. Andrew showed up quickly, and offered to try to use a plunger for me so I didn't have to pay his minimum fee for the auger. He tried valiantly, but to no avail. Then he tried his auger and even that didn't work. He had to end up pulling the toilet and run a long snake. He finally got it cleared, reset the toilet, and cleaned up everything spotlessly. He told me the prices up front and tried hard to save me money. 

When he was going in and out of the house to his truck I apologized because I had to keep locking the door after he came in because the wind kept blowing it open, even though it was latched. He said casually, "Oh, I can fix that for you too." And he did! 

So, I am super impressed with Husted Plumbing! I run a small business in Santa Barbara, and just by the nature of the business, we have a fair amount of plumbing calls. From now on, I'm calling Husted!

categories: Thai, Restaurants
text:
It's a very small dimly lit restaurant but I kind of like it. I always get seated at one of the booths in a corner and it's quite nice.

The pad thai here makes my mouth water. I think it's the best pad thai that I've had in Santa Barbara. I got the yellow curry and it's okay. I'm quite disappointed that they charge you extra for meat. I mean, I know some places charge you extra for rice, but at least they don't charge you for the meat. Even after paying extra for the chicken, I found that it was rare in my curry. Mostly the curry was filled with onions and hard potatoes. It was really sweet, so if you don't like sweet curry, maybe you should reconsider. Moreover, the curry was liquidy like soup (I like my curry on the thick side). Also, rice doesn't come with your curry, so you have to dish out extra cash if you want some. The good thing is, you get free refills if you ask for it. The restaurant lets you adjust how spicy you want your food to be, but I have found little differences in the most spicy and the least spicy.  Everything was basically not spicy at all.

The service is inconsistent. Sometimes the waitress would be nice to us, and other times, they would ignore us. One time, five friends and I came in to have lunch, and they charged us 18% gratuities for lunch so watch out if you were planning on doing that. I mean, I would have expected it at dinner, but I think lunch was a little extreme since no one else was in the restaurant at the time but us.

categories: Restaurants, Italian
text:
I visited Santa Barbara and the nearby Montecito this summer with my Italian-born husband.  We were searching for a good Italian restaurant that night as I was craving some good pasta. Santa Barbara's State Street had a lot of options, but was mobbed as it was Independence Day Weekend.  I searched Yelp and found this restaurant.

Oh my, am I glad I gave it a chance!  The food was to die for my husband said and this is coming from an Italian.  They had more specials than regular menu items.  He had the fettuccine al salmone, fettuccine with salmon in a tomato sauce and my dish, while I can't remember the name exactly (linguine alla zucca con gamberetti, maybe?), was egg noodles in a pumpkin sauce/puree with shrimp.  Both dishes were PERFECT though we agreed that my dish was better as the flavor pairing was just amazing.

As far as pricing, we found the restaurant priced well below what we thought it should have been for the quality of the food.  Both of our dishes were under $15.

Santa Barbara is a five hour drive from us and we'd come back for this place!

categories: Real Estate, Home Services, Property Management
text:
The apartment we rented was expensive for the space and quality. Before moving in, the floors, walls, and counter was chipped. Additionally, the paint job was so cheap that it peeled off even if you left paper on it. The walls were very thin, which made the apartment very cold in the winter. So overall poor quality apartment for such an expensive cost of living - but that's Isla Vista I guess. 
It was only worth it because we had 3 people living here. 
Maintenance is very quick - although we had to send in a maintenance request 15 times this year compared to only once in my previous apartment. It was nice though because they rarely bothered us. 
I wouldn't say I regretted living here, but don't expect the best quality of living.

Lost $550 from our security deposit for cleaning and paint. We very thoroughly cleaned the apartment and lived there for one year.

text: Shared breakfast here with family and friends. You order at the window and then find seating. We sat outside on their lovely patio, the Cali sunshine and their tunes help to make it a very memorable experience! Now to their food... Amazing! text: AMAZING meal. Just stopping through, after flying Cleveland to LA. What a happy accident! We were referred by our hotel because Roy serves late night. We were just happy to have food! However, we ended up BLOWN AWAY by what Roy offered. We shared the crab cakes and the stuffed salmon. Being "foodies"(I know, I know), we are used to great meals, but this food was some of the best; if not THE BEST we have had. I didn't want the meal to end, even though I was exhausted from the flight and drive here. The service was excellent and Roy even came by to say hello and give us tourist recommendations. The best ending to a long day of travel. I would definitely recommend this place to anyone who loves good atmosphere, friendly service, and phenomenal food. Great job, Roy!!

text:
We came for a late night pizza craving same time last years visit. This time a little later at 9:30 p.m. knowing that they were closing at 10:00, we were greeted ans seated at the pizza bar with open arms. In some restaurants we've tried to dined at the last minute, the restaurant/staff werent happy, NOT this place, thank you Roxanne.

We ordered a couple Peroni Draughts, a Diavola Pizza (tomato sauce, fresh mozzarella, spicy salami, gaeta olives) and a Boscaiola Pizza (tomato sauce, fresh mozzarella, mushrooms, fennel sausage) Pizza is absolutely fantastic!

Pizzas, service, atmosphere excellent!

Itsuki is one of my favorite japanese restaurants in Santa Barbara. It's relatively cheap comparing to the other ones here, such as arigato, sushi teri, etc.

I love their salmon kama. It's the BEST salmon kama i've ever had and it's cheaper than the other restaurants. They also have really good ramen (both hot and cold), although they dont have much meat. (I'm a meat lover!) 

But itsuki is definitely worth a try if you are craving for japanese food in santa barbara.

The most romantic and delicious meal I have ever had.  My fiance and I could not have been happier with the entire evening.  The food was wonderful!  I highly recommend the escargot, which was seasoned perfectly.  The wine list was to die for and the chocolate souffle was heaven.  Our waiter was incredibly knowledgeable about the food, the wine and the area they were from.  He was super friendly, attentive and made excellent suggestions throughout the evening.  The decor is simple and romantic.  My fiance and I sat on the covered patio and really enjoyed the decor and fresh air.  Our overall experience was a 5/5.

I can't wait to go back!

text:
I love this place.
 My husband and I came here for our two year anniversary. It was our first time here and i must say they gained two new regular customers. Our waiter was Ryan, he was nice and very friendly. The setting was very romantic but  family friendly. We had the calamari to start which just melted in your mouth. For the main course my husband had the wild boar pasta (sorry I can't remember the name of it but it was f%@!&ing delious) and I had the pesto fettuccini with shrimp. The food was so amazingly good. I told Ryan the food was so good that we would be back Friday and we kept our promise. 
We came back tonight but we had to bring our sister and brother-inlaw. Our server was Justin; he was great. He kept up with all my husband's corny jokes.
I must say the food was  once again to die for. This time I had the roasted Marys chicken. The chicken was sometime I have never tasted before. It was so  delicious. The skin of the chicken must have been caramelized with brown sugar because it was sweet and just the right amount of crispy. My husband had the Steak. It was cooked just right and he didn't want the taste to go a way.
I love this place and we will for sure be back again and again!!!!
Great service and even better food

text:
Quaint little breakfast and lunch place.  You step up to the window to order your food.  Then grab a seat, and your food will be served to you in a few minutes.  My friend and I sat outside since it was such a lovely day. 

My friend's Tugboat (eggs benedict made with a butter biscuit) was served by a runner, who brought a napkin and silverware with him, which was helpful as there weren't any at the tables.  A different runner served me my YOLO (butter biscuit topped with a fried chicken breast, fried egg and smothered with country sausage gravy), but my runner didn't bring any silverware nor napkins.  I had to get up and fetch a set for myself.  Hmm...

My friend enjoyed his Tugboat but had to get extra Hollandaise sauce, possibly because the biscuit is drier and denser than your traditional English muffin.

I found the YOLO to be just OK.  Good flavors with the gravy, but the thickness and the dryness of the biscuit seemed to hamper the enjoyment of the biscuit.  I ended up leaving 3/4 of the biscuit in the bowl.

text:
Excellent seafood place.  After reading some reviews from other yelpers I decided to give this place a try with minimal expectations.  I was pleasantly surprised.  The place is at the end of Stearn's Wharf and super small so I totally understand their system of the sign-up sheet outside.  The staff there was friendly considering the number of people they were accommodating.  We didn't pig out because it was lunch, but the 2 things that were clearly excellent and worth mentioning are as follows:

1) Mussels - If I was self-fish I would say it's "awful" (evil grin), but it's absolutely not.  I've never had mussels that were as large, juicy, tender, and that perfect before.  Granted I'm no Anthony Bourdain foodie, but this was impressive.

2) Clam Chowder - it was very delicious.  Large chunks of clams and yes, it's "horrible" - not!!  It's not overly creamy at all and you can taste the subtle clam juice in there which Goldie-Locks would say "it's just right."

Overall, I would definitely recommend this place to friends and will visit again!

text:
We absolutely loved our mini-adventure on Little Toot! 

The captain and First Mate stopped Little Toot next to a rock where several sea lions were acting extra cute, to the delight of everyone on our vessel. 

Later, we stopped again to witness a convention of pelicans atop a giant bolder. The pelicans were within the hand's reach from us.

Our youngest passenger got to navigate the Little Toot boat for several minutes, under a watchful eye of the Captain, amidst the high seas! 

So much excitement! So much fun! The trip is only 10-15 minutes long, but the experience is outstanding! Little Toot is more than a water taxi- it's an adventure vessel. We can't wait to be back!

text: The great food merits a four star rating. It's the owner Rick's enthusiasm and care for his guests that nails a 5.  We visited on a Monday morning and in addition to receiving a great breakfast, one of our group complimented Rick on the music he was playing in the restaurant. Good food it turns out is only one of Rick's passions. Music is the other. Rick and our table mate conversed about music, specifically jazz, as Rick hurried about the restaurant greeting new guests, delivering generous and delicious meals and always refilling beverages. We told Rick we would be back for breakfast the next morning and he promised to have jazz oriented music playing. Promise kept!  Don't miss the opportunity to drop in for a great meal. If you are into music, let Rick know, it will add to an already great experience. By the way, as we left the restaurant, all four of us received hugs and his genuine appreciation.

text: Dined here on Sunday 7/24/11 with some friends before we went Kayaking.  I ordered their patty melt on sourdough bread.  It was pretty decent.  I just found the patty to be a little bit on the overdone side.  Onion rings were good as were the french fries.  Portions are a little small for the price you pay. The next time a staff member came by was when they came to deliver the check and pick up plates.  On a happy note, they do serve good ranch dressing.  LOL!  :)

text:
The lobster roll was fantastic. A bit over seasoned and the "sauce" quickly attacked the integrity of the delicious roll the lobster came on, meaning the further in I got the messier it became. 

Fish and chips is typical for the area. A decent offering but not the same as those from the Queen's lands will remember. Batter just doesn't have the crispness I yearn for. It the fish was fantastic and the chips were great. Pineapple slaw was decent. Could have used more of the namesake fruit. 

The chowder side was a VERY thick and creamy rendition of the New England classic. Quite good but definitely heavier then I'd want next time! 

We need to return and try the classics this restaurant is known for. While our two diversions today didn't hit all the notes perfectly, they were still good enough to make us want to come back and try the grilled fish our server was recommending when we sat down. 

The free sourdough bread baskets were one of the highlights of the meal!

text:
This was the best wine tour in Santa Barbara we have ever been on. We loved that the wineries were Eco-friendly and small production so they were all unique and there were a few wines that we loved and had never tasted anything like before. Every tasting felt private and the staff pouring spent time explaining the wines, winemakers, and history of the vineyard. Scott was incredibly knowledgeable and shared his passion about wine with us to make sure we had the best experience from start to finish. It was so fun spending the day with such a great tour guide and friend. 
What made it even more special for us was that Scott took the extra time to help my boyfriend plan his proposal at our second vineyard. It was the most beautiful and romantic place and Scott arranged a tour of the vineyard for us. My boyfriend proposed in the middle of the vines and Scott captured everything on camera. He even had a bottle of champagne to celebrate and set up a beautiful picnic lunch by the pond. It was a perfect day and one that we'll never forget. We are so grateful to Scott!!

name: Joy P Bean
categories: Real Estate Agents, Real Estate, Home Services
text: Selling or buying property along the beaches of Ventura and Santa Barbara is a very expensive and complex project. Having expert advice is critical. I hired Joy Bean of Sotheby's international Realty to help sell our beach house that had been in the family for 60 years. We followed her advice, from preparing the house for sale, pricing, staging, marketing, all the way through to a successful close. She worked tirelessly showing the property, and expertly handled all of the negotiations, contracts, inspections and problem - solving involved in our multi million dollar sale. Most importantly, I realized a sales price that was nearly 30% higher than previously estimated by other realtors interviewed. name: Square One
attributes: {'Ambience': "{'romantic': False, 'intimate': False, 'classy': False, 'hipster': False, 'divey': False, 'touristy': False, 'trendy': False, 'casual': True}", 'RestaurantsPriceRange2': '3', 'OutdoorSeating': 'False', 'RestaurantsDelivery': 'False', 'HasTV': 'True', 'BusinessParking': "{'garage': False, 'street': True, 'validated': False, 'lot': False, 'valet': False}", 'BusinessAcceptsCreditCards': 'True', 'Alcohol': "u'full_bar'", 'RestaurantsTakeOut': 'False', 'RestaurantsAttire': "'dressy'", 'NoiseLevel': "u'very_loud'", 'RestaurantsReservations': 'True', 'GoodForKids': 'False', 'RestaurantsGoodForGroups': 'True'}
categories: American (New), Restaurants
text:
Square One is easily the best restaurant I've tried in Santa Barbara and it's the only place I've been to multiple times. Coming from San Francisco and being a serious foodie, I was worried about the quality of restaurants in Santa Barbara, but this place has squashed my concerns. (Did you catch my food pun there?)

The food is prepared beautifully and they do a good job of including interesting ingredients. The portion size is just right for putting a few smaller plates together or going with the more traditional entree and a side.

The service is excellent too. I go in when A. is working (not sure she wants her name online, so I'll just call her A.) She's friendly, attentive, knowledgeable and personable. 

A couple more notes: their website is disaster, but I'm told they're working on it. Also, yelp rates Square One with four dollar signs ($$$$). This is a mistake. It's $$$ at most.

categories: Comfort Food, Asian Fusion, Chinese, Tapas/Small Plates, Noodles, Thai, Restaurants
text:
The perfect place to go for excellent food accompanied by a vibrant atmosphere of Santa Barbara locals and visitors alike. For those living in Santa Barbara that have not had the pleasure of eating at Empty Bowls, make it your next dinner destination and you will not be dissapointed. If you are visiting Santa Barbara, this energetic eatery should be floating at the top of your list of places to eat. It's located in the Santa Barbara public market which is basically a collection of outstanding locally sourced eateries and shops. It's a hot spot for anybody interested in checking out a more authentic side to Santa Barbara away from many of the big name vendors on State Street. 

Food Recomendations:

-Thai Curry Noodle is my life. It's the perfect amount of spicy and creamy and I just can't. 
-Spring Rolls. For the healthy diner that still wants a delcious punch of flavor. So. Effing. Good.
- Three words: Thai Iced Tea. That is all. 
-Literally anything on the menu. You need to go here and try it for yourself because YES.

Atmosphere:

 Shout out to the servers Christina and Dakota who are both literal rays of positive energy. This place get's busy sometimes and there isn't a lot of seating, (its all at a wrap around bar where you get to watch the meals being created, but you can take it "to go" and still eat in the public market designated eating areas,)  however, the staff is super friendly and as long as you enjoy fun people and people watching, the SOMETIMES slightly slower than quick wait time won't even phase you. 

Check this place out! You will not be dissapointed.

text: Thanks for the call back! Service is above and beyond! . I've been having problems with my water meter for months now. With the drought still in full effect, I can't explain how much better it feels to have this taken care of and I would recommend any homeowner struggling with water management to give Gary a call. Now leak free it is worth the peace of mind alone. Thanks Acme  Detection!

text: I came here after suffering a concussion and mis-alignment of my lower back, as the result of being rear-ended by a big truck. My head was hurt so badly I could barely read at half the speed I'd been able to previously. Dr Adam and his team of professionals explained to me in straight scientific terms the nature of my brain injury. They showed me simple exercises to do at home to get on the road to healing. Furthermore, they are the best chiropractors perhaps in the entire country. Most highly recommend!

categories: Cocktail Bars, Fish & Chips, Nightlife, Seafood, Restaurants, Bars
text:
Another reason to miss Santa Barbara. 

The good: The view -  I've been blessed to not have to wait a ridiculous amount of time to get an outside table. The boats, the ocean, the mountains. Super awesome. OYSTER SHOOTERS - If an oyster topped with Worchester sauce, fresh Parmesan cheese, spicy cocktail sauce and Tabasco, served in a shot glass sounds good to you order about 3 of them. If it sounds just ok or weird to you, try 1 just to see if you'll like it. If you don't like them here, you won't like them anywhere. They're cheap and oh so yummy. The clam chowder - ridiculously good, oh so flavorful...you won't be disappointed. The best thing here though is the CIOPPINO. If you don't like it, never, ever read any of my other reviews because you and I just won't get along. 

The bad: On the weekends and tourist season you might have to wait a while to get a table. The fish and chips are just average. The catch of the day is fresh, but nothing special. If you get an inside seat when it's busy it just feels like another fish restaurant...seriously, never eat inside, stand at the bar on the outside if you have to.

categories: Mexican, Vegan, Restaurants, Vegetarian
text:
This is the most variety I've found at a vegan café. Every one of their 5 protein options was substantial and well-seasoned. 

It's set up to be like a vegan version of Chipotle, and they have surpassed them in flavor. I opted for the al pastor, which has a rich spicy beef flavor with a hint of cinnamon. 

The nacho cheese is a common one you find in vegan circles -- the potato, carrot, nutritional yeast base kind. It was above average. I prefer mine a little creamier with some cashew nut, but I imagine restaurants try to stay nut free. 

Portions are huge and guac is abundant. Need I say more?

name: California Hobbies
attributes: {'BikeParking': 'True', 'BusinessParking': "{'garage': False, 'street': False, 'validated': False, 'lot': True, 'valet': False}", 'RestaurantsPriceRange2': '4', 'BusinessAcceptsCreditCards': 'True'}
categories: Shopping, Hobby Shops, Toy Stores
text: California Hobbies is to my knowledge the only hobby store on the central coast from Paso Robles to Ventura and in my opinion it's the only one that belongs! Ken, the owner is extremely knowledgeable and always willing to go the extra mile to make his customers happy. I have bought countless rc planes, trucks and accessories from CH over the years and have never had an issue with any of them (except for my own pilot error haha). As a local of the Santa Ynez Valley, I have the option to order from major online retailers and get things shipped to my door in two days or make the 40 minute drive to Goleta to California Hobbies. 9 times out of 10 you can bet your a** I'm going to make the drive. This store is just that worth it. Yes the prices are marked up slightly from what you see online but that is 100% understandable due to fact that it's not cheap to run a business in a high traffic shopping center. There is always abundant parts inventory for a wide variety of brands and there are countless options of ready to run trucks, cars, planes, boats, helicopters, models, trains and so much more I can't even think of off the top of my head. I applaud California Hobbies and I believe other hobby stores should follow in its footsteps!

text:
I had an amazing experience at Toma! It definitely met my expectations. We had a reservation at 5:00pm and it was packed shortly after. Note - definitely make a reservation ahead of time. 

Our waiter was very friendly and made great recommendations. We had the olives, calamari, tuna cones, and artichokes to start. The lemon aioli on the artichoke was very tasty. The King Alaskan salmon special was cooked to perfection. 

We didn't think we had room for dessert but when our waiter brought the trio sorbet and creme brulee to our table, we couldn't resist. It was the best decision!

text:
The Cheshire Cat is a group of Victorian houses set among graceful gardens in a quiet residential neighborhood.  It is beautifully maintained; it's clear that someone there takes great pride in the place.

The rooms we were in (called Tweedledee; they do keep to the Alice in Wonderland theme but they don't overdo it) were out back in the Coach House.  They were clean, comfortable, and quiet.  We slept like logs.

The staff was polite and very helpful, and the breakfast was ample and tasty (good coffee -- a rarity). 

The inn is close to the center of SB (we walked there); it's hard to imagine a better location.  They have all the maps and brochures to help you find what you want in town, and readily helped us find things when we needed them to.  A great place to stay in Santa Barbara.

text:
Strolling around Santa Barbara, my family and I decided to have Chinese food for lunch. We yelped for local places, and came across this one. The reviews made us a little reluctant, but figured we'd give this place the benefit of the doubt. 

For starters, the overall atmosphere isn't terrible. Fairly clean compared to majority of Chinese restaurants we've been too. Staff was friendly enough. 

When it came time to order, we decided to get dim sum. They give you a slip of paper and a pencil. You check off which (and how many) of each item you want. We ordered maybe 6 items and it took about 45 minutes for them to come out. Not trying to be too whiney, but with our experience eating dim sum, the food usually comes sooner. And the taste was kind of bleh. In the end, we wouldn't come back or recommend this restaurant.

text: When I arrived at the hotel the room was clean, nice and perfect.  My family and I left to have dinner downstairs and the  food was great. The bad thing was when we got to our room my daughter noticed that there was a big giant bug on the wall beside her bed. It looked like a giant tick. The animal didnt move it just stayed there. I called the front desk and told them there was a giant looking tick on my wall. I wanted to change rooms right away. They said there was nothing they can do and that they couldnt change our rooms. They said they can come to our room and kill the bug. I was sooo dissapointed. I killed the damn bug myself and I couldnt sleep thinking there was more bugs in the room. We didnt stay another night. Our vacation was cut short because of that stupid bug. Next time I visit Santa Barbara  I am not staying in this hotel.

text:
A word for my fellow vegans. I know we'd usually steer clear of a place that boasts of 4 pages of menu mostly containing fish and meat. I nearly did too. Except, that I was with a group of friends and had to go to this place. I was quite happy with the end result. I managed to be in a corner and the waitress was v attentive to making sure I had my order in while the rest of the table got their meat and fish game going. 
I got the seared Japanese eggplant, and shishito peppers for appetizers, and the mediterranean roll for the mains. They were all v good and fresh, the Mediterranean rolls were innovative. There were a handful other vegan options that I was considering, but this was more than enough food for me. The presentation of the meat and the fish dishes for the rest of the table looked grander, and more well thought of- they must not get many veggie/vegan orders perhaps! I'd come back here for the vegan options, there are many others I didn't try.

text:
This is a less than great LA dining experience, without the drive.  Food is good, not sensational.  It's very fussy & overpriced.  Service is hovering & lacked flow.  General manager is right out of a sitcom - super tightly wound with an arrogantly abrupt attitude.  Somerset reeks of a vanity project that's trying way too hard without delivering - it's all package, no present.

For an upscale, true Santa Barbara dining experience, I'd suggest the Stonehouse restaurant at the San Ysidro Ranch, Bouchon, Downey's, Lucky's or the Lark ahead of this venture.

text:
This is specific to Sansum Clinic Travel & Tropical Medicine Center.

I can see why their google review ratings are awful. Left a message last week and finally got a call back. Only to be told we need to make an appointment to figure out what you need. I'm a patient of Sansum, my shots are current and listed and wanted to know if I need extra vaccines. 

The rep who called me back was a scheduler, not a medically trained professional so obviously he had NO idea what to do other than that we needed to schedule an appointment. I can't help you, you'll just have to go to the CDC website and figure out what you need. 

I'm CALLING YOU because you're my medical provider. Any one can just go to the CDC website - thanks Captain Obvious. He proceeded to tell me to just go to Walgreens and they'll figure it out.

Well - you clearly just pointed out that your entire department is obsolete and easily replaced by a provider like Walgreens. Good to know. Maybe Walgreens will have better service.

text:
Fish and Chips? We had to stop by since we were in a fried-errific kind of mood, we of course ordered the fish and chips with a side of baked beans; it was perfect, with little visible signs of oil and grease, the fish and potatoes were fried to perfection. Even though the fish was covered with batter, the size of the fish was a very generous size, each bite that I took was heavenly, flakes of fish smoothly came off as I took each bite, so good! 

The Haggis on the other hand, I didn't know what it was, but the mister remembered that his Scottish coworker kept telling him to try it one day. So today was the day, even though it was from a fast casual dining establishment we were still down to try "haggis". And it was delish, like a meat pie, loved it! 

What I found on Google: Haggis is a dish containing sheep's 'pluck' (heart, liver and lungs), minced with onion, oatmeal, suet, spices, and salt, mixed with stock, and traditionally simmered in the animal's stomach for approximately three hours. --- yes that's what a haggis is, and I fell in love.

Backyard Bowls is the best! Great Acai bowls in a cute space. I was led here through the advice of a friend who loves the place. And by advice I mean he demanded that I go here and check it out. Im glad he did because it was a great find! 

Ummm...... So I kinda fell in love with bee pollen. I had a few tastes of my friend's backyard bowl and absolutely fell head over heels for it. Who knew bee pollen could be so tasty? 

I had the berry bowl and my friend had the backyard bowl. I thought mine was awesome, with yummy acai smoothie on the bottom and slathered with honey and goji berries and homemade granola, topped with fresh fruit. It was bomb diggity! 

Im soooo gonna return the next time Im in Santa Barbara.

My first appointment with Jeff this past weekend.  Before meeting him, I was impressed with his professional website and presence. I have had massages worldwide, and have a lot of experience with different modalities and approaches.  Based on my needs, Jeff really helped me.  We discussed my background, immediate body challenges and suggested approach.  My 1.5 hour was heavenly, and just the right amount of work for my aching back. (I am a full time sailor now, living on our boat and passing thru town to Mexico) We visit SB often and I will return to see Jeff when I can.
I know there are hundreds of massage therapists in the SB area; Jeff is one I will refer to my friends.  
Thank you!!

This one in particular had a Spanish style vibe with the archways, the tiles, the open door patio, French doors to the bathroom, etc. I loved that bathtub was open to the bedroom, it had a romantic feel. The valet service is beyond accommodating and super friendly. They are attentive and nice. They do have an overpriced coffee shop next to the lobby area. What I did not like was the amount of insects (which I know is expected) but just on the walls chilling, made me anxious. But it has a beautiful pool, nice towel service, walk to the beach and hiking trails. It is serene and a great escape.

text:
I had really high hopes because I heard great things, but I was really disappointed with my drink. I ordered a strawberry rose milk tea (which I usually get at boba stores that allow you to customize your own drink flavors) and every other store gives me a milky, fruity light pink drink. But I got a drink that was BARELY milky. I wouldn't even classify it as a milk tea. The flavoring is all just really dense syrups and it's wayyyy to sweet. They over did the sweetness and I can't imagine what it would taste like if I got a more potent flavor (like passionfruit or lychee). Maybe this place has great fruit teas, but as for milk teas, this was a huge disappointment.

Also, the employee was extremely rude. Maybe she just was having a bad day, but she forcefully handed me my drink and didn't even say anything. She just walked away without any form of customer service interaction and coldly shoved the drink on the counter.

text:
Nothing but positive things to say about Sandbar! To start off, the ambience provides such a refreshing and relaxing setting. The service is always great, very friendly and attentive servers and the food and drinks are delicious! You can't go wrong with any of their margaritas but if you're not a margarita person they have a huge menu of other tasty cocktails to try! Every time I go to Sandbar I will myself to try something different to eat and I haven't been let down yet! (and don't expect to!) Everything is so flavorful and cooked to perfection. 
I would definitely recommend checking out Sandbar for a relaxing lunch/dinner or a fun night of drinking and dancing!

The food was meh and expensive. Cool atmosphere, but really not worth it.

text: Came in today with some out of town friends on a little foot tour of the sights in Santa Barbara. We just wanted to grab a few pieces of salt water taffy so we went in and picked some. No greeting, girl was hiding in the back and when it came time check out it took quite a while for her to come over to the register. She was extremely unfriendly. While getting my money out my purse accidentally pumped the tip jar and she looked at me like I might as well have shit on her shoes. I apologized and she just stared blankly at me. Awful experience. People come in first for the food but they return because of the service....and views!
 
Gotta love the college life.

name: Calvin Kim, DMD
attributes: {'ByAppointmentOnly': 'True', 'BusinessAcceptsCreditCards': 'True', 'AcceptsInsurance': 'True'}
categories: General Dentistry, Health & Medical, Cosmetic Dentists, Dentists
text:
I had a huge cavity under a crown. Dr. Kim proved to be gentle, knowledgable, and skilled. He has leading edge technology: the new crown was milled on site and fitted 20 minutes later! AND he takes insurance. He is a good listener who answers all questions intelligibly.
He drilled out the old crown, dealt with decay below the gum line, all and then fiddled with the 3D pics, filling and removing on the  model right there in front of me. It was mesmerizing! He loose fit the new crown, adjusted it slightly, and voila, all done. Thank you, Dr Kim!

name: Best Western Plus Carpinteria Inn
attributes: {'WiFi': "u'free'", 'BusinessAcceptsCreditCards': 'True', 'RestaurantsPriceRange2': '2'}
categories: Hotels & Travel, Event Planning & Services, Hotels
text:
I've always liked this hotel, but after my last experience over Christmas weekend I will have to think twice about staying here again. The 1st room was nice at first, until we had complaints about the noise, yeah ok noise . You wanna talk about noise?!?! 2nd floor was bouncing around all morning 5am-11am. We told front desk and apparently the did nothing about it , so we had them switch us rooms. And now this leads to my other complaint, I left my watch in this 1st room and went to get it back after we switched rooms....and of course it was gone!!! I left on the bedside table. By the time I realized it was gone the maid service came and cleaned the room, so I know they took it . I never wore the watch and never took out of the room ...it doesnt just disappear!! So yes Best Western STOLE MY Watch !!! and it wasnt some cheap watch either !! Your lucky I didnt press charges, thanks for nothing Best Western..next time Im staying across town

If somebody from Best Western would like to send my watch back, please do so. Or a nice check to cover my watch will be acceptable as well. Your move Best Western

This place is great! It's run by a bunch of Vietnamese people who are very skilled at what they do. The girl who did my nails had only started working there a few months ago, but she could have fooled me. She was very nice and we had a good conversation. It was funny because she started the conversation by asking me, "You Chinese?" just as every other Vietnamese nail salon has. 
Went on a Thursday afternoon with no appointment, but I'd recommend booking one because they were packed. 
I got a French mani -$20 pretty cheap for SB. 
Orly for the tip, didn't pay attention to what the pink was, and seche vite top coat. Lasted a little over a week!

name: The Ritz-Carlton Bacara, Santa Barbara
attributes: {'BusinessParking': "{'garage': False, 'street': False, 'validated': False, 'lot': False, 'valet': True}", 'BusinessAcceptsCreditCards': 'True', 'BikeParking': 'True', 'ByAppointmentOnly': 'True', 'RestaurantsPriceRange2': '4', 'WiFi': "u'free'", 'DogsAllowed': 'True', 'BusinessAcceptsBitcoin': 'False'}
categories: Restaurants, Beauty & Spas, American (New), Event Planning & Services, Hotels, Massage, Resorts, Day Spas, Hotels & Travel, Venues & Event Spaces
text:
My dearest friend and I came to the Bacara for a well needed mama vacation. We chose the Bacara over Ojai Valley Resort to enjoy cooler weather, ocean views and to experience the spa. 
Unfortunately majority of our stay was very disappointing. For being a 5 star hotel, and the prices to go with it, the food at the main bar was horrible. The drinks, especially some of the house drinks had to be sent back as well as the food as it seemed the bartenders were not experienced. They were also out of several types of popular alcohol. 
The food at the Spa Cafe was decent and the staff there was attentive but we felt as though we had to stick to that restaurant to ensure that the food would be good quality.  
We felt that the management for the restaurants and bar was non existent and it showed in the service and the presentation. 
We did get a treatment at the spa and the massage therapists were attentive and did a good job but again we were expecting a 5 star treatment but did not feel it. We took a fitness class but the instructor was not very professional. The grounds and the buildings were well taken of and were breath taking and we enjoyed the hike and walks around the property. We will not be returning nor be referring to this hotel to anyone wanting 5 star service.

text: Always love the food at Giannfranco's! The paninis for lunch are very yummy. Went for dinner this past week, and got: lobster ravioli, beet salad, and their special for the day (a pasta with seafood)- all delicious. The short rib and chicken parm are also great selections. Chicken parm comes with angel hair pasta as well. The atmosphere here is lovely- the owners are friendly and come around to chat with you, and they have both outdoor and indoor seating. One caveat is that on the night we went, seems like they were understaffed, as we had to wait a bit before our water was brought to us, and also a fairly long wait time to take our orders as well. But everything else was amazing- would definitely come back!

name: Kevin Schmidtchen
categories: Real Estate, Home Services, Real Estate Agents, Real Estate Services
text: I went to look at one of Kevin's listings today, 3172 Lucinda lane. When I walked into the house, he made eye contact with me, and instead of greeting me, he quickly looked away. Strange. As I walked through the house, he made eye contact with me a second time, and again quickly looked away without acknowledging me. While I was perusing the house, another woman came in, and he quickly greeted her and energetically spoke with her for several minutes. The only explanation I can imagine for his behavior is that he was judging me by the way I look (shaved head, no high heels or lipstick, unlike the other woman who came to see the house), or didn't think I was attractive enough to acknowledge. This is incredibly bizarre behavior for an agent who is trying to sell a home. I am looking to buy in the San roque area, and will absolutely never consider any home he is representing. Every prospective buyer should be welcomed into the home, acknowledged, and treated with respect. Clearly Kevin doesn't agree.

name: Deux Bakery
attributes: {'RestaurantsPriceRange2': '2', 'BikeParking': 'True', 'BusinessParking': "{'garage': False, 'street': True, 'validated': False, 'lot': False, 'valet': False}", 'BusinessAcceptsCreditCards': 'True', 'RestaurantsDelivery': 'True', 'RestaurantsTakeOut': 'None'}
categories: Bakeries, Food, Desserts
text:
In from out of town and in charge of some festivities, I was pleased to get a last minute birthday cake order for next day pick up. I asked Deux for a simple 8" vanilla cake with butter cream icing. Not much icing. Very simple. 
The pickup was seamless, 55$(!)  but the cake itself was very dry and hard-ish inside. The icing might have been butter cream but was not sweetened at all so it tasted like ... well butter and cream. It was piled high on top with elaborate all white flowers and had piping around the top and bottom. Lots of frosting. 
When we cut into it, all the icing fell off the sides in small slabs, making for a messy presentation to dinner guests. The icing tasted rich and bland. You didn't want to eat more than a taste.
I had been looking forward to having an excellent quality sweet-ish fix ( not what I eat regularly) so I am disappointed! I would freeze individual slices but it's not worth returning to this taste experience. Sorry. But thanks for taking the last minute order.

categories: Restaurants, Mexican
text:
Mony's is a popular hot spot in the Funk Zone.  I have gotten food from here a couple of times and have not been disappointed.  They are generally very busy because the food is so good and the prices are great.  The portions sizes are huge and this family owned business takes great pride in preparing all the foods that come out of the kitchen.  

The restaurant is small but there is some indoor and outdoor seating areas, nothing fancy but comfortable enough to enjoy the delicious food.  On this visit to Mony's we picked up an order of the loaded Carne Asada Nachos.  This nachos were more than enough for the three of us.  The meat was tender, the chips were fresh and crunchy and the beans and other toppings were an explosion of flavor and tastiness in your mouth.

The food was so good the following morning we ordered the Carne Asada Burrito to take with us on the "Jump on the Bus" ride to Santa Barbara Vintners Festival Grand Wine Tasting in Buellton, CA. 

This burrito was awesome!  It was the kind of burrito that takes two hands hold and a wide open bite to make a dent in it. Need I saw more, it was fantastic!

text: This is a top notch piano studio.  I travel from Arroyo Grande to Santa Barbara to have my kids learn from Vera.  This is a long drive for us, but worth it. I have researched many teachers and she is one of the best on the Central coast, in my opinion. She teaches piano playing, music theory, sight singing/reading and so much more.  Your child will learn to play with finesse - this is rare.  Other teachers can teach you how to play notes, Vera will teach you how to play from your heart and evoke emotion.  I am the church pianist and a former director of music education for the Santa Maria Philharmonic Society.  I expect the best from my teacher and Vera is definitely one of the best.

name: California Avocado Festival
attributes: {'GoodForKids': 'True'}
categories: Local Flavor
text:
Spur of the moment mini road trip.

My husband read about the festival in some travel mag.  I wasn't too enthused at first but figured I could pick up some recipe ideas.  

It's a nice little food festival.
Not as many booths featuring avocados as I thought there might be though.
Had a BLT with guacamole sandwich which was just awlright.  $7

Bought some Halloween wreaths in one of the artisan booths. $5 each.
Got a bottle of avocado oil.  $10
Caught a very cool drum circle performance.
Had some New Age-types in tie-dyed clothes asking to touch my hair.
(I was in a good mood so why not.)
Browsed through the shops that lined the streets in the area.
Saw some cute dioramas made by local kiddies with dressed up avocados.
Looked at, but didn't touch the prize winning big-ass avocados (2-3 lbs).
Got some free avocado slicers, recipes & travel guides.
Forced myself to use one the many port-potties.  Got ticked off when I discovered I could have gone inside the Vons down the street.
Hubby always buys festival T-shirts.  $16  They gave us a free "go-green" shopping bag which was cool.

It's a lovely (but windy) community & we enjoyed the visit.

One complaint:  On the website I looked up the directions on how to get there.  The directions take you straight to a festival parking area.  $10 which includes a trolley ride to the event.  We figured to go visit the city's beach afterwards.  So we drive towards the shoreline.  We find free parking next to the beach.  We look behind us.  WTH?!?  The back entrance to the festival was right down the block!  Okay, they suckered us-Haha.

text:
As a native New Englander walking around in Montecito I was drawn to the little deli by a Red Sox sign. As I walked in and saw a Tom Brady jersey and a Boston Bruins cap I felt I was home. 

Up until that moment I was struggling for an inspiration for lunch.   That was settled now time to eat. 

They have a nice variety of menu Sandwiches but I just stick to the usual, a grilled chicken wrap.  The salads behind the case all looked great and since I was in California I figured a fresh fruit salad would be nice. 

Everything was fabulous. 

Nice people and nice table outside Ina beautiful fall day. Can't ask for more. 

Go PATS!!!

text: My wife and I arrived for an early Monday afternoon, we we're seated on the patio after a few minutes. We were promptly greeted by the waiter, whom seem to think we were immediately ready to place an order with an attitude as if we were an inconvenience. We asked for a minute to read over the menu, since being our first time but asked for waters. He acknowledged and walked back behind the bar to continue a conversation with his coworkers, clearly forgetting our request.  After 10 minutes he returned with the same cavalier attitude as before, but realized he'd forgotten our waters. We ordered cocktails since we were tired of waiting, which seem to jog his memory of our previous order. The waters and cocktails arrive shortly after. My wife acquired about an appetizer she saw on yelp since it wasn't on the present menu. We were told it wasn't available, kinda discouraged we said we needed another minute. We were surprised when he returned a told us " the kitchen can make a special request and make our order".  This made things better. After that the rest of the experience went well and the food was great. All in all, I'll probably return but I'll be make sure I'm ready with my order before I'm seated and I'll just have to overlook the unneeded cavalier attitude.

text:
Fresco's is the shit. Pardon the language, but it is. Come in the evenings when there's usually some jazzy little ensemble outside playing music. Despite being in a little shopping plaza along with Ross and Albertsons and the like, the atmosphere in this little corner is excellent and definitely feels a lot fancier than you'd think for the location. I liked taking dates here.

Food changes daily so there's plenty of variety and it always tastes fresh as well as has this grandmother-y, home-cooked essence. I use to work across the street at the Starbucks a long time back and knew a few of the workers at Fresco's. We'd trade frappacinos for soups and such and it was one of the best perks of working at that Starbucks. Try a little of everything as I've never had anything bad here but my personal favorites were the calzones and the creamed corn soup.

The one thing that really, really, really sucks about Fresco's though: it's closed on Sundays, which seem like the best day to have this kinda food. Always annoyed the heck outta me, haha.

categories: Restaurants, Nightlife, American (New)
text: My husband and I had reservations for 7:00, first visit, got there about 6:45.  One couple was in the main dining room. We waited for several minutes at the reception desk while one hostess argued with someone on the phone and the other said they would be with us shortly. Finally the 2nd hostess moved the other away from the computer to check our reservations and then sat us at the table next to the entry door and the reception desk.  We asked to be moved to another table and she grudgingly snapped up the menus and took us to the back dining room, again one other couple in the entire room, and sat us at the furthest table back, next to the exit.  Guess she didn't like us asking to be moved.  Water was served and split on both the floor and table and no one cleaned it up.   I had the chicken pate for an appetizer and it had practically no flavor.  Had the entre sized salad ($18) and it was so swimming in dressing I could not even eat half.  My husband had the entre salad for his appetizer and the hamburger for the entre, which he liked, but was the size of an overgrown slider.  The rosemary fries were good.  The waitress was good and knowledgeable about the menu.  We definitely will not be going back as there are so many other wonderful restaurants in Santa Barbara and our experience at the Arlington Tavern was a disaster.  The bar was packed so I guess that is the reason to go.

text:
We came here tonight, the Saturday of Memorial Day weekend, as a group of 5. We were expecting to wait at least 30 minutes but we were seated in less than 10 with a cool
View of the kitchen! The decor and ambiance of this place gets 5 stars. 

As for the food, the highlights were the tuna ceviche (I could eat that everyday for the rest of my life), the crab cakes and honestly...... the complimentary sourdough bread. It was warm and crunchy with a soft interior. I know that sounds crazy, but the bread was seriously a highlight. As for entrees, the rockfish was tasty and the seafood sampler plate had a nice variety. The side of brussel sprouts were also a hit. My sea bass was a little tough and over cooked. For dessert, skip the cheesecake and go with the blueberry bread pudding.

I'm subtracting a star for service because while they were busy and definitely working hard, it just was so clumsy. They auctioned off plates at the table and some orders were incorrect. Our server seemed a little new and inexperienced. It just wasn't as slick as I would have liked for a place where you're paying $35+ per person. But overall, fast and friendly service. 

I really liked lure and will definitely be back here or to their other locations!

text:
They say that imitation is the sincerest form of flattery.  Is that true?  Do you really believe that?

My visit to this establishment could be considered as a form of flattery then, if that's true.  The C., upon hearing of my trip down to SB, mentioned that I should try this place out.  And he was here naught a week prior to my visit.  What better recommendation does one need for a place to grub than from someone you know and love?

I ordered the burrito, and it was HUGE!  That sucker fed me for two days!  The staff are beautiful and friendly (his main reason for eating there, if ya know what I mean), and I passed on his hellos to the girl at the register.  She simply shook her head and smiled.  Whatevahs.

I sat outside on the sidewalk/patio area as I had my boy with me.  The day was wonderful - warm and muggy, though with a slight wind that made me wish I sat around the other side of the building where the sun was shining.

Should I ever return to school, I will definitely make this place a stomping ground.

name: Channel Islands Adventure Company

categories: Rafting/Kayaking, Active Life
text:
Our kayak tour of Santa Cruz island was the best part of our California vacation.  We met our guide Ben as soon as we checked in.  Check-in was super easy.  The ferry ride out was chilly, but otherwise pleasant and smooth, and we even stopped to see some seals.  The sun came out as soon as we made it to Santa Cruz and the weather was perfect.  Once on island the guides led us the campground, helped us suit up, and we hit the water!  We spent the next few hours popping in and out of caves - really unlike anything I've done before.  Ben was a fantastic guide and we felt very safe with him, and he answered all of our questions about the history and ecology of the island.  After the kayaking was over we still had a few hours to hike before the ferry ride back.  

Although we had very little flatwater kayaking experience we did fine on this trip.  I definitely would recommend a day trip to the Channel Islands, and be sure you do the kayaking!!

categories: Pet Stores, Pets, Pet Training, Animal Shelters, Pet Services, Pet Sitting, Pet Boarding, Veterinarians
text: After looking up many boarding facilities that vets had to offer for cats, I decided on the Humane Society. I chose the HS because they have two-story cat cages, with a 'cat cave,' as well as a cat door that leads to a cage outside, as well--The Ritz for cats, if you ask me! Also, the price was extremely reasonable, and for the most part, the staff seemed friendly and caring. The reason I am only giving three stars? Well, when I went to pick up my cat, I could tell she had not been cared for, besides being given the basics, food and water. Her fur was matted and dirty, she had 'lost her meow' (like a person with a hoarse voice), and she had a few scabs located on her head. She has been itching/grooming more than usual, and I put two and two together, and have figured out that she acquired fleas while she was there. Though I know my cat was in a safe environment, I doubt that I would board her at the HS again, but at the same time, would still recommend it to someone on a tight budget.

text:
Dawn Patrol has a casual, surfer themed interior with delicious brunch options. Sporting a focused, yet customizable menu, Dawn Patrol can cater to picky eaters and solidly deliver on breakfast fundamentals.

I highly recommend the breakfast hash, which I customized with Bacon, Scrambled Eggs, Spinach and Mushrooms and was delighted to find it fresh, well cooked, and seasoned properly.

Located on lower state, Dawn Patrol is front and central to all things beach in Santa Barbara. Next time you hit the waves, stop in for a breakfast burrito!

4/5
