text:
Super simple. Super honest. Super accommodating.  Super kind.

Fernando just open his shop not too long ago, but he's killing it.  Excellent customer service, quick turn around and just a really nice guy.  I drove up essentially unannounced and he greeted me like we were old homies, hooked up the machine, ran it, and handed me my certificate all in about 20 minutes.

Also, no charge if you don't pass!  Need a smog test, go see Fernando.

Thanks again man!

categories: Active Life, Wineries, Tours, Horseback Riding, Arts & Entertainment, Food, Hotels & Travel, Event Planning & Services, Wine Tours, Rafting/Kayaking
text:
Most Wine Tasting tours will run you upwards of $100 per person (or at least thats what I saw when I was planning the last trip.  So then what do we do?  We look to Yelp for help and yelp help is what we got!

Captain Jack's specializes in tours for those who love the outdoors and booze.  We did the horseback ride/wine tasting.  

Horseback Riding was partnered with a ranch that has horses to take you though SB canyon.  They treat you like newbies (which we were) but aren't condescending about it.  They make it fun despite the pain of the trotting horses.  Rocket, I will miss you! (My horse) Until next time!

The wine tasting was only going to 2 different tasting rooms which was kinda of blah but was still fun.  Our driver took us to Kunin Wine tasting room and Coastal Winery.  We ended up buying a bottle of d'Asti from the Coastal winery.  

Our driver was really cool and kept a good conversation going on the whole time without intruding on our own private conversations.  The best part is that he picked us up and dropped us off at our hotel.  A MAJOR plus for those who like to "Taste" a lot of wines.

If you want to do wine tasting in SB, definitely check out Captain Jacks, great prices with knowledgeable guides.

PS, I think they raised the prices since I booked.  I paid $200 and their site now says $300.

text:
SBB Gourmet catered my wedding in July 2012 and it was absolutely perfect!

They tailored the menu to meet our loose "Midnight in Paris" theme, yet kept everything very Santa Barbara appropriate for our outdoor ceremony at the Santa Barbara Historical Museum.

Miniature Croque Monsieur and Shrimp Toast passed appetizers, Brie & Mixed Greens Salad, Seasonal Grilled Vegetables, Grilled Chicken & Beef Tenderloin. Oh the Beef Tenderloin! My husband's family are huge meat eaters and EVERYONE commented on how amazing the carved-to-order meat was. Tender and delicious. Definitely not "wedding food"

The pinnacle though was their execution of my request for a cheese "wedding cake".

Instead of the traditional cheese display appetizer, I requested different sized wheels of cheese stacked to look like a small wedding cake. A wonderful staff person manned the station and sliced the cheese wheels to go along with the crackers, nuts, honey and antipasti also part of the display. It was absolutely gorgeous.

They then disassembled the "cake" and made beautiful bread boards that went to each guests table for them to snack on between cocktail hour and the serving of the meal. They were well organized and handled our combination of "served" and "buffet" reception. They served the plated salad, manned the buffet and carving station, then came back to serve coffee and champagne. All this was coordinated flawlessly, allowing our guests to feel waited on and cared for. All this from a satellite kitchen they had to set up, as our venue had no established kitchen. 

I could not be happier with SBB Gourmet catering. Their food was excellent, their service superb I would suggest them to anyone searching for a wedding or other event caterer in Santa Barbara.

text:
Is it possible to give a zero stars rating? 

My husband & I have visited the Sandbar every time we have gone to Santa Barbara for the last few years. The food is not anything amazing, the service was less than amazing but the atmosphere was always fun so we always returned. This past trip, when my husband approached the hostess stand, the hostess informed him she could not seat the party because of the tattoo visible on his neck. This is bizarre for a number of reasons - 1. We've been there at least 5 times before with never so much as an incident. 2. Nowhere on the Sandbar website or Facebook page can I find anything on this (&I'm quoting the manager here) "Corporate Policy". 3. Other patrons had visible tattoos on arms, legs, backs, etc. Hmmm THAT"S ODD. This, to me, is blatant discrimination. Perhaps they will find something about you they don't deem "acceptable" - maybe you dye your hair, or wear contacts, or have a religious affiliation they just can't make any room for. Whatever it is- whether or not you have tattoos (which I don't!), I would NEVER EVER RECOMMEND GIVING YOUR HARD EARNED MONEY TO AN ESTABLISHMENT THAT SO BLATANTLY DISCRIMINATES AGAINST FORMER, LOYAL PATRONS. It's despicable. & there are many, MANY other great bars with better food & better service on State Street & in the Santa Barbara area.

name: Santa Barbara Zoo
attributes: {'BusinessAcceptsCreditCards': 'True', 'RestaurantsPriceRange2': '2', 'GoodForKids': 'True', 'BikeParking': 'True', 'DogsAllowed': 'False', 'ByAppointmentOnly': 'False', 'BusinessParking': "{'garage': False, 'street': True, 'validated': False, 'lot': True, 'valet': False}", 'WheelchairAccessible': 'True'}
categories: Zoos, Event Planning & Services, Venues & Event Spaces, Active Life
text: My third stop on my adventure in Santa Barbara was here. After dreaming of animals the prior night, it drew me here. This is a tiny gem. This little zoo is beautifully landscaped and set up. The thing I noticed and enjoyed was that the zoo had kept up with technology. Around the animal exhibits were smart phone video links containing even more information on the animals. They're those little blocky bar-code type-picture things that smart phones can read and decipher. They also had hand-crank-powered recording boxes. After pressing the button, the hand crank would be turned and it would answer the question you were interested in. A neat little device. The animals are well cared for, the exhibits are informative and spacious, and it's a fun place to visit. My Santa Barbara adventure was going strong, but nearing it's conclusion.

categories: Chinese, Cafes, Taiwanese, Restaurants
text:
Let me preface this by saying I am, sadly, inexperienced with Taiwanese cuisine. When I first looked at their menu, I wanted to order everything, but we figured out how to narrow it down, sort of! We ordered fried dumplings, popcorn chicken, an onion pancake with egg, bento box #1, mapo tofu and an onslaught of drinks (red bean tea, lychee tea, Yakult tea, caramel pudding tea and wintermelon tea). 
My girls devoured the fried dumplings and popcorn chicken (the chicken was good, but the curry sauce they put on the side made it excellent)! The onion pancake was my favorite; the flavor was spot on and I couldn't get enough! I was really surprised by bento box #1. For starters, it looked so nice (I know that means little in regards to taste, but I love when food looks neat), but the pork itself was also fantastic! It has a slightly sweet taste that reminded me of the filling inside bbq pork bao. I didn't even bother to share the sausage, it was so good. But, I did relinquish my hold on the corn and kimchi. They did not hold back on the spices of the mapo tofu. Wow. Maybe I'm getting weak in my spicy game, but i was having to take sips of tea every few bites to wash down the heat! My only complaint was that it needed some salt (easily remedied with soy sauce), but the sauce itself could've used some.
The drinks were all delicious and slightly too sweet, though this seems to be on trend with most boba tea spots I've gone to. This was our first time trying wintermelon (my daughter is obsessed with the candy, but we hadn't seen it as a tea). It was very good. It tasted like a southern sweet tea with a slightly smoky aftertaste. I'm a sucker for red bean ice cream and  loved the tea (I also asked for extra red bean on the bottom because I am all about the texture). I was disappointed in the Yakult tea. It didn't have that milkiness I was expecting; it didn't taste bad, it just wasn't what I've had on previous occasions. The caramel pudding tea (with extra pudding of course) was also slightly too sweet. It tasted better once the ice had all melted. I love that they have pudding though! It adds such a unique texture to drinks and I was happy to see another spot that actually carried it. I do wish they used the sealed tops that allow you to shake the tea before putting the straw in. It makes things easier on the customer for take-out.
Thank goodness this place isn't that far of a drive because we will be trying the rest of the menu real soon!

categories: Bars, Venues & Event Spaces, Event Planning & Services, Wine Tasting Room, Arts & Entertainment, Food, Wine Bars, Beer, Wine & Spirits, Nightlife, Wineries
text:
I can't say enough good things about these folks. Their wines were fantastic. I am not much of a white wine drinker, but even their white wines were enjoyable. (They had flavor, not just that annoying fruity candy tang so many white wines taste like to me.) The people were so friendly and knowledgeable about wine, and didn't come off the least bit pretentious. I love that!

My favorite was the Deep Sea Red so I bought a bottle to give my boyfriend as a present and when I found out it had been corked and gone a bit vinegar-y (an unavoidable fluke in vino manufacturing) I called and they shipped me a new one right away. Their customer service was really amazing. 

Seriously, this place is super easy to miss on a walk down the Wharf, but if you do happen to see that sign labeled "Wine Tasting"and you have a minute to relax with a bit of wine, walk up through the gift shop (whose name I don't remember) and back to this little gem of a tasting room with unbelievable views of the Pacific ocean. You won't regret it.

categories: Restaurants, Mexican
text:
What a great find in arguably the most sleepy part of Old Town Goleta!

I had been to this restaurant a number of times when they were under previous ownership. While the food and atmosphere were both good, the service had always lacked a bit. That being said, it was still good enough for me to want to go back. I was happy to see that they reopened some year and a half later under a new owner. Naturally, I had to give it another try.

Walking in, the decor was much the same as before. The dining room is dark but clean. I always opt to sit on their amazing back patio that has been tastefully upgraded with plank flooring and a nice lanai area. The uncovered section was shaded by a gigantic avocado tree which provided just the right amount of sun and shade. It was still just as nice as before.

Our waitress was very sweet, knowledgeable of the menu, and checked on us often. The food we ordered was seriously amazing. I ordered chicken sopes and they were so tasty. Fresh ingredients, awesome presentation, and they had a wonderful flavor. My coworker had ordered the Chile Colorado lunch plate and raved about its flavor as well, along with the fact that the accompanying tortillas were fresh and still warm. Yum! Prices weren't bad either - average was in the $10-$15 range.

I believe that this place is still in a soft opening phase as they seem to be working to acquire a liquor license. It may be off the beaten path a bit (located on a quiet side street that can be easily missed), but I'd definitely recommend trying it out if you're on the hunt for quality Mexican food with killer service. You won't be disappointed.

This is Santa Barbara's newest and hottest food delivery service in town, and is a MUST TRY for anyone who loves great quality and taste of food!

text:
Mandarin Palace has impressed me lately with their affordable lunch specials so naturally it deserves a good review! I honestly hadn't stepped foot in here for many years because it just didn't appeal to me anymore but thanks to my co-workers wanting to come here for lunch I've become hooked on it again.

The lunch menu prices are mostly $10, and for the amount of food you get when dining here it's totally worth it! I've called in my order and taken it to go but honestly if you dine-in you get way more food which includes their soup of the day, salad, crispy wonton chips, and hot tea upon request. 

The service here has always been good to us, and the food is served in a reasonable amount of time so you're not going to be rushing if you only have an hour lunch. It's never been so busy that you can't be seated right away. 

I've read mixed reviews on this place and depending on whether you're dining here for lunch or dinner I guess it varies, but my experience has been good overall so no complaints here! I'm no expert on Chinese food but this place serves up delicious food in my opinion.

text:
Wow, had to go to this place on the 4th of July, outside it looks nice, read the menu and it wasn't exciting but the host is very warm and nice. I don't like ripping a restaurant but here it goes.

Waitress states the Salmon is all fresh (I know Salmon does not run this time of the year and it's going to be frozen) so she lies, I also know most - not all Ravioli is frozen. So like idiots we order one of each and are massively disappointed.

1st course Cauliflower soup, verdict over over over salted, swardfish soup extremely salty and you can tell it was frozen - defrosted just a shame.

Entree's, the salmon  was soft but it was frozen soft, if you really know fish, you would know the difference, my Ravioli's were simply frozen - cooked with a watery sauce. We complained to the waitress and I told her she should try the soup herself. No reply, I understand Santa Barbara is an LA a rip off vacation place, but this place is a joke. I am sure it's a money maker but if it was a local only place they'd be out of business.

So, if you want frozen dinners in a nice outdoor setting go here!

Perfect date spot for those who like stiff/classic cocktails, good meat and an authentic/retro ambiance. 

I enjoyed the fillet and my date's prime rib was on par (pun intended) with other steakhouses I've visited. Meals come with the traditional-- soup, salad, side (potatoes, pilaf, etc) choices. The wait staff is straight out of the 70s and awesome. 

Dimly lit, big leather booths-- perfect way to go if you're looking for something fun, good food and eclectic atmosphere.

text:
10/10 would recommend

My friends and I came on a drizzling day but that didn't stop us!!! The alpacas are so cute, you get to play with them and feed them carrots. This is fun for all ages! Some of them even have sunglasses and hats on. 

The tour was about an hour long, you get taken around the farm where you can also play with dogs, there's also chickens lol.

You end up in a cabin like store where they sell things like scarves made from alpaca fur and other goodies. The cabin overlooks Santa Barbara with a beautiful view.

categories: Hotels, Event Planning & Services, Hotels & Travel
text: Very cute, a bit funky, nicely landscaped courtyard, very clean and has a small pool, well-maintained. Perfect location on State St, across from a high-end shopping center with a gourmet supermarket and good restaurants. The manager lady was great. I had to return and extend my stay after a medical emergency. She gave me the same great (cheap) rate I got for mid-week, online, even though it was the last available on a busy weekend and was one with a kitchenette. Very honest businesswoman and very informative about events and directions. Room was clean, wifi great signal, the free breakfast was adequate. King bed was very comfy. Unless they raise the rates, I wouldn't bother looking for another place to stay in Santa Barbara; this is the place.

categories: Restaurants, Chinese, Szechuan, Soup, Seafood
text:
This new Chinese restaurant is run by Mr. and Mrs. Hong; who are the previous owners of Mandarin Palace. 

I came here to try out their lunch specials and decided to order the Almond Chicken. For starters I was served the soup of the day. It had flat noodles and veggies. It wasn't too bad, but it was very different from the traditional egg drop soup.

Next was my main meal the Almond Chicken. This was served on a large tray that included one egg roll, one cream cheese wonton, fried rice, salad, and some kind of weird white creamy concoction that looked like it had canned veggies. I was afraid to touch it, but it had my curiosity, so I took a small bite and yet I still couldn't figure out what it was! So I asked the waitress "What is this exactly?" And she kindly replied "It's the chef's special". According to her it's a traditional side dish that's served in their family and they wanted to share it with the customers. It wasn't bad but it was just kind of weird to me because I've never seen anything like it. Interesting is all I can say!

The Almond Chicken was pretty good and tasted fresh, there was nothing fancy about the fried rice but it totally reminded me of Mandarin Palace. Loved the cream cheese wonton! The salad was very mediocre. I'm not a huge egg roll fan but it was crispy and fresh.

Their dining tables seat 4 people, and mostly everyone dining here during lunch was solo. It was funny to see one person at every table that seated 4 people! Luckily it wasn't busy but I can imagine if it had been busy then you probably wouldn't find a seat.

Overall I would come back here again to try other items on the menu but for now I'm rating it 3 stars. BUT! I give Mrs. Hong 5 stars for her great customer service and warm welcome.

text: Went because of the stars on Yelp and because the prices weren't nearly as viciously through the roof as most spots in Santa Barbara. Nearly empty as we were there early. Charcuterie plate: meh. Server didn't explain anything on the plate as is typical for this dish and it clearly lacked a spread (oh wait, they pre-coated the 4 thin crisps with something green, meaning you were stuck with that as the only bread/cracker) - sorry but for $15 for a small plate that's not ok. My chop salad was pretty good but my husband only finished his fried chicken sandwich because he was really hungry. Cocktails? Poor. Bartender please learn how to make a basic old fashioned and don't pack the glass with ice so it's immediately watered down (was not given choice of bourbon either which was odd). While our impossibly perky server was fine at the start, she never asked how our meals were and we were left dawdling at our table for a good 10 min after finishing our meal with napkins on the table etc. For $70 they could have definitely stepped it up in some easily fixable ways.

text: I would only give this place a 1/2 star.  What a horrible dinner!  I ordered off the menu, shrimp with marinara sauce and angel hair pasta.  Can you believe it came out with a plate of angel hair, boiled shrimps with a sweet marinara sauce siting on top.  If I wanted shrimp cocktails, I would have gone to a sea food restaurant. How hard it is to make this simple dish???    I asked the waitress to take it back and she offered to have the cook put the dish back in the pan and may be blend it all together.    What a disgusting dinner!  I sent my dish back and told the waitress, it was inedible.  My kids had their dinner, spaghetti with 5 tiny meatballs and 3 cheese raviolis- which they were fine with.    When the check came, they have the nerve to charge me for that gross dinner!  The waitress said she can only take 1/2 off and I would need to speak to the manager.   The manager came over and told me I should not have ordered off the menu.   Well, if the dish was too complicated, then the waitress should have informed me other  wise.  She said she can't take the entire dish off my bill bc they rather me get something else.  After several minutes of explaining to her why I refused to pay for a dish that was inedible.  And mentioned that I will write a very bad review like this one then she decided to go ahead and take dish off the bill, but proceed to charge me $4 for a few pieces of garlic bread.  I'm never coming back and beware of what you order.

text:
I've been told to come here by so many people, and I finally had the chance! It's an upscale bar and restaurant that is still pretty casual. So dress up or dress it down, however you feel, you should come on over. 

My friend and I started out with Yelps offer (when checking in) for the free order of garlic fries! A huge bowl full of garlic covered fries with a delicious dipping sauce. I COULD NOT stop eating them!! 

We asked for the waitresses opinions on cocktails and ended up going with the Spirit of the Riviera (vodka, hibiscus syrup, lime, and cucumber) and the Frida in Love (roasted citrus reposado tequila, grapefruit, lime, habanero, agave, with habanero sugar/salt rim). We have never had such amazing tasting cocktails, but then again we really have never been to a fancy cocktail bar. 

Then we decided to share some other orders off the happy hour menu, all kits $7 each! We had the deviled eggs and the roasted Brussels sprouts. Perfect sizes to share with a friend so that you can try more of everything!

text:
I'm not exactly the healthiest person who would seek out fruits as a fun snack, but I have really grown a fondness for Backyard Bowls. I LOVE IT!

I've been here a few times now, and every time I would only get the kid's sized Berry Bowl because the other sizes are too much for me :3 I actually find myself craving for this on a hot afternoon when I wake up too late for breakfast and I'm not hungry enough for lunch. Ordering was never a problem; it was right in front of me before I knew it. And yes, please add extra honey.

All kinds of sweet, sour, crunch, and cool in one great acai bowl.

text:
The 'foot' spa is a nice idea as they give you a full body massage, but the atmosphere is not serene or quiet as many others I've experienced has been. It's on State Street and loud!

If they could get more mindful massage practitioners and a more peaceful setting, their business would sky-rocket.  It's wonderful to get an hour massage (fully clothed) for $30!

The clients were left to wait in the middle of the massage while discussions were carried on within the store.  The business owner was also loud and I'd travel further for a better experience. (Sunrise in Ventura has a nice quiet setting on Main Street)

If you don't have anything to compare it to, it's ok.

categories: Breakfast & Brunch, Venues & Event Spaces, Peruvian, Event Planning & Services, Bars, Nightlife, Latin American, Restaurants, Cocktail Bars, Seafood, Tapas/Small Plates, Mexican
text:
In order of favorites:

1. Pork Belly Quesadilla - 
A MUST GET! When we got it, it didn't look like the usual quesadilla where the meat was drench with cheese.  It almost looked like a smothered taco.  I've never seen pork belly in a quesadilla so it definitely worth trying!  Take it from all the yelp reviews, you won't regret it.

2. Bistec a lo Pobre - 
Kobe beef skirt steak, chimichurri, quail egg, crispy polenta, grilled knob onions.  This was a surprise, actually.  I did not know what to expect out of this one and it came out delicious.  I would highly recommend this dish.  Eat all the components together and you'll get a burst of flavors and textures in your mouth.  Party in your mouth!

3. Oyster Shooters - 
My first ever so I don't have much to compare it with, but the waiter said their oyster shooters are a little different than the ones you normally come across.  It was really tangy and delicious.  
 
4. Empanadas de Camaron - 
Mexican white shrimp, mexican cheese, tomatillo-avocado sauce, mango-habanaro glaze with chipotle aioli.  The shrimp was deliciously cook, nice and tender.  Thought this was delicious.

5. Vanilla Bean Flan - Thought the vanilla bean was a great touch to the traditional flan dessert.  I thought it was a little on the sweeter side for my taste, but we still finished the whole thing.

Came here on a weekday night and the place was not packed and parking was easy to find.  Not sure how it gets during the weekends.  

The outdoor patio area is nice and relaxing as there is a fountain filled with turtles and fishes.  

Great date place.

text: This is my third out of town annual visit to Downey's the past three years.  Our 12/9/15 visit included five of us to celebrate the holidays, including one who has severe allergies. We went here for our anniversary lunch. This place was absolutely amazing!!! Everything was absolutely perfect!

The service was outstanding! 

There was an incident when we were there. 2 older Russian Armenians women decided to order a ton of food, eat to their hearts content then rudely scream at the staff and not pay their check. They obviously had no intent of paying their check given they ate like 3 full baskets of bread (even though they said the bread was awful), a whole order of oysters (even though they said it was undercooked and they were going to get sick) and like 2 plus extra plates of food. All the plates were literally licked clean. Those awful women kept insulting the staff and harassing the management. We had to move our table. After, the manager approached us and apologized profusely for those disruptive women. She then offered us a free dessert for all the trouble! 

You can't beat the service here! The food was cooked to perfection. Big portions! Ordered the cedar plant salmon and shrimp cocktail.

text:
We were excited to check out the new natural wine bar and bottle shop in Santa Barbara. The design is unique and beautifully done. Inside the seats are sexy and lean towards the nighttime. The garden patio in the back was adorable. Reminded us of a Brooklyn patio or New Orleans patio with brick walls, windows, vines and lots of plants. All of their wines are non-interventionist. They have several wines by the glass and the bottle prices are totally reasonable. They also have a cocktail menu. We decided to try a "wine cocktail" & they were fantastic. We started with "Kiss the Boot" and the "Real Wild Child". They were both so good we decided to end our right with two more cocktails ("The Gentle Whip" and "Black Leather") that the server referred to us. Refreshing and not too sweet, perfectly balanced and the right amount of bitter to end the night. During dinner we tried several wines that blew our mind. We decided to buy a few bottles to take home for future enjoyment. We were very surprised how delicious the food was for a wine bar. They source everything locally. Small plates that are great for sharing. We had the garden fritters with olive babaganoush, cucumber gazpacho with spot prawns on top, ricotta dumplings that I will dream about and ended with the ganache. They had other options like fried oysters, summer melon salad, rabbit, and lamb belly. The main food menu ends at 10:00pm but they have late night snacks until 12:00 am. Food prices ranged from $5 to $21. The menu is full of quirky lines and the cocktails all had fun names inspired by rock songs and lyrics. Even their tables were custom with Velvet Underground lyrics on them. It's clear someone has spent time curating the perfect 70's and 80's rock music to go with their vibe. You'll hear artists like Bowie, Blonde, Iggy Pop, The Clash, & Lou Reed. The staff was very knowledgeable about wines and gave great customer service while keeping it casual and fun. We look forward to adding this cute bar to our rotation of going out spots in town. 

This spot is IT.

text:
So it's about time I got a yelp and what better way to start then by giving a review to one of my favorite eateries in Carpinteria. Being a high school teenager the main issue I encounter is that I need to eat a lot yet I have little to no money. 

 The moment upon opening Taco's Don Rogue has been a favorite among local youth and everyone else. It's quality food at a cheap price. The simplicity of the business model is ingenuous. A variety of tacos and a variety of salsas. What else do you need? I have tried every taco to salsa combination they offer from carnitas with don rogue to lingua with Diablo (extremely spicy). The food is made to order and the toppings like onions cilantro and radishes are always fresh.

 The only disappointment I had was there increase in prices now making a single taco 1.60. Which is still cheap compared to the price of tacos else where. It came as a surprise as my normal 6 tacos came out to  a little over 10 bucks. Overall Don Rogue is still the best place to fix a taco crave as well enjoy a quality meal.

Not one moment in the cafe did I feel welcomed.

categories: Restaurants, Mexican
text:
If I could hand write a love letter to Lilly's Tacos, I would. Lilly's is the rock of my life through both good and hard times. Two lengua, one adobada, and a lime Jarritos, please. Wait 1-5 minutes, and you have all you need in life. 

First, Lilly's makes consistently great tacos. Every single time I come here, their quality never changes. The salsa, quality of meat, etc. is spot on each time. It is not a place to go for infinite options. It is a place to go for good execution of a handful of favorites. Their steamed selection is particularly good. 

Second, Lilly's is fast. Line out the door? No problem - still lightning fast. I've never had a long wait, or trouble finding a seat in the spacious living room. 

Third, the people are all-around fantastic. The folks taking your order and the ones in the kitchen are genuine, kind people that treat every single person that walks through their doors with respect. They work really, really hard to make sure everyone has an excellent experience. 

Fourth, Lilly's is a good value. It's one of the very few spots in Goleta/SB that you can have a great meal for two under twenty bucks. As a student (or anyone else trying to get by in this town), this is a godsend. 

Fifth, this place is spotless. The walls aren't laden with art or decorations, but you can bet that when you sit down at any table it is perfectly clean and neat. I don't know how they manage this with so many people coming through the doors all day.

I could go on and on... really the only thing I don't like about Lilly's is that they're closed on Tuesdays. But they are working hard all during the week, so I guess they've got to take a break sometime! 

Top menu favorite is the lengua. It's outrageously tender, with just the right texture to soak up plenty of lime and salsa. Perfection. Unlike most places in town, they DON'T charge a dollar extra for lengua. Thank you, thank you, Lilly's! Other things worthy of trying are the adobada (marinated pork... its crispiness makes it the perfect counterpart to the lengua), and cachete. The only thing on the menu I don't adore is the extra crispy tripas... a little more on the deeply browned side than I like them. Still, I see lots of people order and love those! Their tortillas aren't homemade or anything special, but they taste just fine and do their job. As an Arizonian who was spoiled with seriously excellent, affordable Sonoran-style food, Lilly's is pretty much as close to the quality of home as I can get. 

Overall, if you're in Goleta and looking for a tasty, quick batch of tacos with no stress for parking, Lilly's is the best choice.

text:
I found Dr. Rugg after reading an article about her work in the Newspress. My dog had an accident the weekend before I read the article, and I saw numerous specialists, then I saw Dr. Rugg. She gave me frank and insightful guidance to develop a treatment plan, I've followed her instruction and my dog is recovering well. 
She offers dog acupuncture, my dog had a back injury, Dr. Rugg is the best in SB for this! If your vet recommends surgery, get a second or third opinion! There are other safe options, it's worth the affordable visit.

text: This is a hidden gem in Santa Barbara when you're looking for authentic German food. Went here for dinner and they have a great selection of German and Belgium beers. I ended up ordering the Knockwurst and I tried the Schnitzel. The wurst was delicious, although next time I'll be going for the Brat. It came with potato pancakes, which were as amazing as they sound, some veggies, and a whole bunch of sauerkraut. Yum. The Schnitzel was also a must try. As for customer service, it's seat yourself, and our waiter Ian was the most pleasant, optimistic person I've ever met. A+ service.

text: Chose to stop by Pickle's and Swiss for a picnic sandwich to take to the beach upon arriving in Santa Barbara. I was so disappointed with this place.. my friend recommended the Gluten-Free pancakes, saying they were delicious and fluffy- I was SO excited.

I came in and ordered, this was maybe around 11 AM on a weekday, so it was slow (maybe 5-6 other people). First off, the pancakes were over 13 dollars.... I was hesitant to pay so much, but my friend's recommendation made it sound worth it, so I forked over the cash. Then, it took ~25 to 30 minutes to get my order, and it was SO quiet in there, I have no idea how it could possibly take that long. Then, the pancakes were skimpy, flat and TINY. There were only 3 of them, and they were barely bigger than silver dollar pancakes from IHOP (and not even as good...). 

So, 13+ bucks and 30 minute wait later, the pancakes were super disappointing and I was still hungry... Sorry but I am not coming back. :(

categories: Greek, Restaurants, Mediterranean, Food, Beer, Wine & Spirits, American (New)
text:
I wish there was an option for half stars because I would give this place 2.5.  I have been 2 times in the last month.  I went in December, probably with the same group as Richard W.  I belong to the Santa Barbara Newcomers Club.  We have a membership of over 600 members and have been around for 60 years.  We have a sister org named The Graduates that has several hundred members.

We go to different restaurants on Friday nights for Happy Hour.  The attendance is anywhere from about 40-50 people to over a hundred.  I went to Petros in December and had a mostly pleasant experience.  The flat gyro appetizer is very good.  I didn't like the calamari (not a fan of fried olives).  And there wasn't much calamari; mostly fried veggies.  

The place was crowded because of us and it was difficult for others to get through but the restaurant didn't have many guests that were not part of our group.  I felt ignored by the bartender most of the night.  And when I asked for a glass of water (I was sitting at the bar), I was told I had to serve myself at a little table in the next room where they put water glasses and a pitcher.  Not what I would consider good service at all.

Then our group was there this past Friday night, the 16th.  Well this night was, IMO, an absolute disaster from a service perspective.  Again, we were probably about 75 or so folks.  They gave us a long table in the corner of the patio (again not many others in the place) but instead of being served at the table, we had to go the service bar to order and wait for our food.  The bartender/owner was very rude and seemed very unhappy.  Most of the servers seemed either caught off guard or clueless.  There were 2 of the servers that seemed attentive.  I wish I knew their names.

There was such a bottleneck of people by the service bar, waiting for their drinks and food, it looked like utter chaos.  I couldn't understand why they couldn't serve us at the table like we were normal customers.  I felt like we were being treated like the wicked step-children and didn't have the right to be served.

This is a group of well-off professionals and retirees.  None of us are uncouth, troublesome or cheap.  This is a group of savvy, sophisticated, well-traveled folks that eat out a lot.  I couldn't believe how we were being treated.  

If this wasn't enough, the grumpy bartender/owner comes over to the table and yells/mumbles out something and walks off without eye contact.  I started asking the others what he said.  Someone told me that he said we had to vacate the table, they had a private party coming in.  No attempt whatsoever to be pleasant diplomatic or polite.  Just yells and walks away.  

Meanwhile, I moved to another table and ordered a second appetizer from one of the attentive servers; the chicken souvlaki.  It was not very tasty, but i ate it.  I kept expecting the server to bring me the check for it because I wanted to pay.

Finally, I flagged him down after waiting for at least 45 minutes and then the grumpy bartender/owner guy comes over and asks me if I want to pay for the appetizer.  Then he said he had to pay out of pocket for all the people that didn't pay for their orders.  I didn't see anyone at the table being given checks for what they ordered and I don't know how many folks got their food by standing in line at the service bar, but I'm sure that no one in our group purposefully didn't pay for their orders.

Not everyone has a good memory when it comes to remembering to pay for food at a happy hour when they're talking to friends, being moved around roughly and having some cocktails.  If that server had brought me the check earlier, I would gladly have paid.  So I wonder how many other people never got their check?  And why is the bartender/owner criticizing my group to my face?

Well, needless to say, our group is going to another local establishment this coming week.  And Petros has lost my business and probably many others.

Someone from our group said the bartender/owner drives up from L.A. everyday to work and that's probably why he's so unhappy and stressed out.  Well if this place wants to be successful, they need to give better service and treat people with respect.

As we were leaving (now an hour or more after being told to leave the big table), there were only 2 or 3 small tables of people in the patio.  The other group hadn't even come in yet.  This restaurant probably seats over 200 people, but when I drive by, I see a lot of empty tables.  I'm sure their rent isn't cheap.  I hope they get their act together so they will welcome business instead of acting like it's an inconvenience to them.

And I've worked in service industry for many years, as well as restaurants.  There is no excuse for what we experienced.

name: Hotel Indigo Santa Barbara by IHG
attributes: {'RestaurantsPriceRange2': '2', 'BusinessAcceptsCreditCards': 'True', 'WiFi': "u'free'"}
categories: Resorts, Venues & Event Spaces, Hotels, Event Planning & Services, Hotels & Travel
text:
Location, Location, Location. Very trendy little boutique hotel in the heart of Santa Barbra. Within walking distance to beach, dining and shopping. Front desk employees were very nice. Hand sanitizer stations all over. Very nice, quaint sitting areas inside and out throughout the hotel to gather. No elevator, only steps (there is a luggage elevator but didn't work). Valet parking that you can pay for. A rail road train next to hotel so you can hear the train at times. I lived in NYC for years, it's all the sounds of the city.

My friend and I were just staying overnight. We booked a King size room. The room seemed clean. Very small, as my friend says "very European feel", it had all the amenities, coffee maker, iron & board. desk, hair dryer etc... Bathroom small, but workable. The Air system is a mini split, worked well when we were there. Bed was very comfortable, good sleep.

I would definitely stay here again.

name: Best Western Plus Pepper Tree Inn
attributes: {'WiFi': "u'free'", 'RestaurantsPriceRange2': '2', 'BusinessAcceptsCreditCards': 'True'}
categories: Event Planning & Services, Hotels & Travel, Hotels
text:
I took my parents here for Memorial Day Weekend a few days ago.  Although, I understand that it was a Holiday where many hotels raised prices to accommodate demand, paying $229/nite, plus tax here was not worth it at all.  Here's why I was unhappy.
 
1) This motel is 2 miles away from beach, where are the night life in Santa Barbara takes place.  One has to either driver or cab it over there.  
2) The restaurant that it is connected to has bland food, along with terrible, rude service.  My mother's tea came luke warm, and when she asked to heat it up, the waitress acted like she was doing us a favor.  
3) Bed bugs and other creatures in the room.  I took a photo of one right in front of the motel manager.  Of course he was surprised, but said he couldn't do anything because I had book the room through a 3rd party app.  This I don't believe this..who owns the bed?  The motel of the 3rd party app?  
4) Aside from the bed bugs, I found a spider and another 4 legged creature on the floor.

This experience was not good nor will I stay in a Best Western again.

name: Spa Concepts Salon
attributes: {'BikeParking': 'False', 'ByAppointmentOnly': 'False', 'BusinessAcceptsCreditCards': 'False', 'RestaurantsPriceRange2': '2', 'BusinessParking': "{'garage': False, 'street': False, 'validated': False, 'lot': True, 'valet': False}"}
categories: Nail Salons, Threading Services, Skin Care, Eyebrow Services, Beauty & Spas, Hair Removal
text:
I first heard of Dee at Spa Concepts through an Indian friend that had gone to her starting a couple months ago.  I don't have much hair and my brows grow slowly.  However, they were in need for a little cleaning up, so I went.  

The first time I went, she said she was going to just shape it so that it looked presentable.  She wanted more hair to work with so she told me I'd have to come back possibly 3 times at least with 2 months in between each visit.  I agreed.  She did ok on my first visit.  The brows looked ok.  When I got home, my right brow looked slightly higher than the left brow.  I went back to her and she told me to let it grow out so she can work with it.  Fair enough.  I ended up drawing in my eyebrows to compensate.

On my second visit 2 months later, she got to see the amount of growth on my brows, and proceeded to shape it.  After she was done, both of my brows looked too thin.  I was a bit disappointed because I had much more brow to work with after 2 months.  After I got home, I noticed that my right eye brow was still higher than my left (despite my telling her beforehand that this needed correcting).  I also noticed that my right brow and my left brow looked like they had different shapes (one had a smooth arch and the other had more of an angle) and both weren't looking symmetrical.  Again, I went back to her to show her what she did.  She said to allow it to grow out and that my brows will really take shape on the third try.  She convinced me that it takes 3 tries to fully get it the way it should be.  Like a dummy, I decided to give her another chance and told myself maybe she knows what she's talking about.

On my third and final visit another 2 months later, I came back to her and reminded what she did the last 2 times.  She said no problem and got right to work.  I reminded her not to make my brows too thin, to make both symmetrical in shape and in position (height), etc.  She kept nodding and told me not to worry.  After she was done, I was shocked to see what I saw in the mirror.  My brows were basically a thin line (about 1/8 inch only!).  I couldn't believe what I saw!  I confronted her politely but firmly about this, and she only said that that was my true brow line!  WHAT?!  I had much more hair to work with after this 2 month wait, and this is what I got?!?  I went home crying and all my husband could do was hold me.  In addition, after I got home, I noticed that my brows were even less symmetrical and that the arch on the right brow is closer to the middle of my forehead than the brow on the left.  I was very sad and angry.  I've been drawing my eyebrows in ever since.  Sigh...

I will never go back to Dee again!  Let this be a warning.  That 3-time thing she told me about likely was a scam.  She charges $20 (cash only!) each time (expensive for brows), and I feel like I really got ripped off.  (She's probably not reporting most of her earnings to the IRS.)  And what is this name she uses "Dee's Spa Concepts"? There is nothing spa-like about her facility...no other spa services offered and her business place is the size of a closet.  I kept trying to give her the benefit of the doubt, but now I'm out of patience.  I'm going to try Layla (downtown Santa Barbara in the Paseo Nuevo Plaza) the next time I need my brows cleaned up.

text:
Five of us had dinner at High Sierra tonight and all were pleased. Three had hamburgers  - Mushroom, Blue Cheese and Sourdough. Two of us had fish and chips. Lots of food. Fish had a nice batter that was the right degree of crispness - not the mushy stuff you get some places. The tarter was bland - but then I zip mine up with Tabasco and horseradish. Malt vinegar and lemon helped. Service was pleasant and attentive. Prices were reasonable. We'll go back, maybe try the back-ribs, which others have said are excellent.
I might add, the French fries were average - a thicker slice might be recommended. Nothing wrong, maybe my personal preference for fewer, larger fries that hold heat longer and provide more mouth-feel. Really, a nit that doesn't detract from the overall positive.

text:
Walked in on a Saturday night after a day of wine tasting in Santa Ynez, and my group was seated immediately (we called ahead to let them know we were on our way).

Menu leans toward the French tip (think Escargot, Steamed Mussels, Beef Bourguignon).  The dining room is open - the walls decorated with diamond shaped, framed drawings that I assume were done by customers/friends of the restaurant.

We started with the fried calamari and steak tartare.  The calamari was your standard lightly breaded variety that came with a side of aioli.  Steak Tartare was good, a small portion of raw ground beef and chopped onion with other herbs/seasonings, served with arugula and bread.

For entrees, I ordered the Mahogany Short Ribs with Baby Bok Choy, and a side of the garlic mashed potatoes.  The short ribs were good, especially when paired with the mashed potatoes, which everyone at the table LOVED.  Probably the smoothest non-fake mashed potatoes I've ever had.

Definitely a great choice when dining in SB.

categories: Nightlife, Pubs, Beer, Wine & Spirits, American (Traditional), Burgers, Bars, Food, Restaurants
text:
AMAZING! 
Now the natural comparison would be to Eureka! Burger but really the two have little in common beyond outstanding burgers, beer and whiskey. 

American Ale is a dark pub with no table service. You order your burgers at the bar and a food runner brings them out (very quickly and efficiently I might add). 

Eureka has many appetizers and excellent entree salads; American Ale does one thing phenomenally well: burgers. Eureka! reportedly spent half a million on the decor/interior and it's bright without being obnoxiously cheery. 

But I am angry at Eureka for taking my favorite burger--the Caprese--off the menu . American Ale offers burgers for the bacon lover as well as carnivores who dislike bacon or who at the very least who would never dream of putting bacon on a burger.

My boyfriend loves the three bacon burger (two are bacon proper, one is Canadian bacon, aka ham which I just plain can't bear under any conditions unlike bacon which on occasion I like in a BLT or a Cobb salad--or the Wolfgang's salad in NYC in Murray Hill on 33rd and Park). 

I don't eat fries as a rule but I had some and they were excellent. They don't have onion rings, which Eureka does perfectly. 

I also don't drink beer but had an IPA I loved in a cute glass jar. 

I love whiskey but didn't have any as I'd had white wine before dinner and in my experience white wine is hangover juice period but certain death when  mixed with beer and whiskey within the same 24 hour period. 

My horseradish and blue cheese burger blew my mind and I will be back. 

As good as Umami burger, which is now my standard of comparison but far sleeker.

text: We've been here twice. First time I remember being fine - not great, not bad. Second time, we walked in and saw that the tasting menu was more whites than reds (we prefer reds) but since the place was empty (Sunday noon), we didn't feel right walking out. So we just shared a tasting. The person was really nice and informative. We sat by the window as we tasted and he even came out to pour for us which was really nice. (We usually just taste and go back to the counter for the next one.) It was a very nice experience. Too bad we didn't particularly like either of the wines tasted. Maybe next time one will hit the spot. Either way, AVA is a nice place to visit.

text: While the jacuzzi tub was very nice, I couldn't overlook the overall shortcomings of the room.   The toilet was in a space so small that your knees will be only a few inches from the door when seated. The door did not have a lock, or even close completely.  There was no closet, only a rod hanging above the dresser with two hangers.  There were missing tiles & the door & window moldings had been replaced, but not painted.   The ceiling fan had a missing cover over one of the lights.  The wifi didn't work. There was no hairdryer.  The tub  & shower are out in the open, so if you're traveling with someone you would rather not see you bathing that should be kept in mind.  I think this may have been a nice place at one time, I cannot recommend it.  It needs some major renovations.

name: Kimpton Canary Hotel
attributes: {'BusinessAcceptsCreditCards': 'True', 'WiFi': "u'paid'", 'DogsAllowed': 'True', 'RestaurantsPriceRange2': '3'}
categories: Event Planning & Services, Hotels & Travel, Venues & Event Spaces, Hotels
text:
We had an awesome experience at this boutique hotel. This hotel has top notch service and supports sustainability. The hotel front desk even communicates with text and you can ask for items, ask for recommendations, etc this way. We received a discount on overnight parking because we drove a hybrid. This hotel is really dog friendly, not only this but there is no additional charge to bring your dog (no size restrictions) AND they even allow you to leave your dog in your room if need be (as long as your dog is not barking, etc). I have NEVER before come across a hotel that allows you to do this. The associated restaurant/bar downstairs is hip and the bar seems to allow dogs too!

The hotel really makes you feel special. In fact, Helen at the front desk even left us a gift of a framed photo of our dog in the hotel. It was a very nice surprise. We were not hotel rewards members and had booked off Expedia, but after our all around great experience, we signed up for their reward program because we will be back!

Perks:
Free happy hour daily in the lobby with local beer, wine and appetizers
Attached restaurant 
Friendly and attentive staff
Super duper dog friendly (the only thing is that there is not any grass on or around the property for bathroom access for your pet)
Access to next door gold's gym 

Location:
In the downtown area, so everything is walkable. This is not a waterfront property, but there is a view of the ocean from the lovely rooftop pool area. 

Note: if you aren't a dog person, this hotel is probably not for you, as there are lots of dogs hanging out at this hotel.

text: We have driven by Rincon Brewery many times, but have always been on our way somewhere. Today, we were looking for a place for lunch and noticed the patio was almost empty right before noon - perfect! Found a quick parking place on the street and chose a place on the patio. Great clean patio, nice view of the street and people passing by. I opted for one of their daily specials, the Cali Burrito - essentially a steak burrito with guacamole, pico de gallo, cheese and french fries....yes, french fries. It came with a side of baked tortilla chips and a great homemade salsa. Would definitely be back next time we are in town!

text: Was here the other night to see a DJ. About half way through the night I noticed someone in our group was missing and checked my phone--he texted me saying he was kicked out because they thought he was washing off his "X's" (they use sharpie to mark huge X's on both hands indicating you're not 21 yet). I went outside and asked the usher kindly to let him back. The usher got very angry and threatened to kick me out as well. I went back inside to test the theory and successfully washed both X's off--PURPOSEFULLY--and did not get in trouble (you still need to have a wristband or ID to get drinks). Went back out again to talk to the usher and another worker comes up behind me and SHOVES me outside. Basically I learned this place would rather be 21+ ONLY so I'm not sure why they even bother mixing the 18+ crowd in there, and a huge screw you to whoever felt the need to shove me from behind outside, you're lucky I wasn't hurt or there would be a lawsuit present.

attributes: {'BikeParking': 'True', 'BusinessAcceptsCreditCards': 'True', 'ByAppointmentOnly': 'False', 'GoodForKids': 'False', 'RestaurantsPriceRange2': '2', 'DogsAllowed': 'True', 'Caters': 'False', 'BusinessParking': "{'garage': False, 'street': True, 'validated': False, 'lot': True, 'valet': False}", 'RestaurantsTakeOut': 'True', 'RestaurantsDelivery': 'True', 'OutdoorSeating': 'None'}
categories: Beer, Wine & Spirits, Wineries, Food, Arts & Entertainment
text:
This places was very cute!
My bridesmaid took me here to kick off my bachlorette weekend. 

Overall: Good wine and great atmosphere to sip on some wine.

Location: It's on a street near other breweries and other wineries. A lot of places were within walking distance. 

Parking: 
We took an uber here, so I'm not sure about the parking situation, but to me it looked like it was street parking, I'm unsure if they had their own lot. 

Wine: I don't remember the prices, if I remember correct, It was $15 for 5 tastings. ( I didn't pay for it, so don't quote me. haha) 
I got to choose from whites, reds or mixed. I chose to try out the mixed tastings.

What I liked: The wine was delicious, they would tell you what you were having before they poured into your wine glass. They also let you keep the wine glass at the end! (They even wrapped it into tissue paper and gave you a bag for it.) 
We sat indoors but I think there was outdoor/patio sitting in the front of the winery if I remember correctly.

They also have this cat that roams around the winery. It's so cute and friendly!!

name: Ronald B Dinning, DMD
attributes: {'AcceptsInsurance': 'True', 'BusinessAcceptsCreditCards': 'True', 'ByAppointmentOnly': 'True', 'WiFi': "u'free'"}
categories: Health & Medical, Dentists, General Dentistry, Cosmetic Dentists
text:
Not big on doing reviews so this says something. Throughout my life I hated going to the dentist, mostly due to my lack of confidence in the person handling my teeth. I will say Dr. Dinning is a super nice guy who really knows his stuff and shows that he cares for you and your oral health. Does a proper and clean job for a more than reasonable price for the work he does. He clearly has loads of experience. I would recommend anyone to come in for general/complex cosmetic work, repairs, and especially assessments which are very thorough. 
Furthermore, the office is very understanding on the financial side as well. Apart from reasonable pricing, I was able to set up a monthly plan to pay off my bill over time which I am not used to seeing elsewhere. 
The accompanying staff match the work ethic and charisma of Dr. Dinning.

text: What a great find. Used to always go to Something's Fishy when I lived here. This is much better. Went with friends while visiting in town and we ordered a ton of things since there was four of us. Some of the things we had: tuna roll, Rock 'n' Roll, Fiesta Roll, Locals Only (which came out flaming, you can't beat that!), Tiger Roll, Unagi Nigiri, real crab California Roll, "Off the Lip" Crab Puffs, Chicken with spicy mustard sauce Gyoza. I lost track we ordered so much. Everything was well prepared, fresh, tasty, and well executed. A real gem in SB.

text:
This is probably the only Thai restaurant in Goleta so we decided to get our fix. The do have a lot of options to chose from. Ended up getting Pad See Ouw with tofu, and egg rolls. The sauce for the egg rolls was a little bizarre, it gave me and my roommate a weird cough after eating it, and not because it was spicy. 
I liked that they made the noodles a little crispy for the Pad See Ouw.
The major downfall of this place is the atmosphere. The walls are tacky with not many decorations, and parts of the restaurant smelled like public bathroom cleaner. Kinda gross. They need to give this place a really really big face lift so people can focus on the good food.

text: The drinks are watered down, so even with their happy hour 2 for 1 special you don't even get a buzz.  I guess this a way to keep the just-turned 21 SBCC and UCSB crowd to buy more drinks without turning sloppy.  Now, if just the drinks were crappy that would be one thing but we ate there the other night and my bean and cheese Tostada tasted like something had gone completely sour.  Literally, it tasted like sour, curdled milk.  I asked my boyfriend to smell it and just the foul scent made him lose his appetite.  When I told the server she took it to the kitchen and came back to tell us that they use a sauce on some of their dishes that might have a similar scent.  I replied that there was no way this could be the sauce, unless that had also gone bad.  I had a terribly upset stomach for the next two days....

name: Big Joe's Tacos
attributes: {'BusinessAcceptsCreditCards': 'True'}
categories: Food Trucks, Event Planning & Services, Mexican, Street Vendors, Caterers, Restaurants, Food
text:
I was lucky to try Big Joe's tacos at a birthday party I attended. I had no idea about them and asked if they are local here in Santa Barbara. Turns out they are based here but do cater out of town as well. 

The menu for this event was as follows: 

Tacos ~ 
Carne asada 
chorizo 
adobada 
chicken
grilled veggies 

They were all delicious! The meats were very well seasoned and not too salty. I just wish the servings of meat were a bit more as they were pretty skimpy. Especially the chicken. It was finely chopped so it almost seemed like bits of ground chicken. I would give these 3.0 stars for the portions but 4 stars for flavor.

Sides ~ 
Mexican rice
pinto beans
chips and guac
salsa

The mexican rice was your traditional rice but it had good flavor and wasn't dry. It was cooked perfectly. The beans were just plain pintos but those are the best when combined with the rice and some salsa to spice it up! 

The chips n guac were just ok. I mostly enjoyed the chips because they were homemade and not too greasy or salty. The guac didn't seem to be authentic but more like the stuff you get pre-packaged in the store. It tasted good despite not being the real deal. 

There were 5 different salsas to choose from. I tried them all and mixed the mild ones with a few drops of the habañero as suggested by Angel the taco guy. I pretty much put each salsa on everything cuz afterall who doesn't love salsa! They were all freshly made and had good flavor. The medium one was a bit watery though. Aside from that I enjoyed each one. 

Quesadillas were also served upon request. I couldn't get over how delicious the chorizo quesadilla was! And the chorizo wasn't too greasy as it tends to be. Such great flavor! I really enjoyed this.

Angel and Diana catered this event and they were very professional and kind enough to explain each food item being served. Their set up was great too! 

Overall if you're looking for a taquero to cater your next event give Big Joe's a try! They really did a great job.

categories: Chicken Wings, Restaurants, Italian, Pizza
text:
I picked Sal's Pizza after reading reviews of several Santa Barbara pizza deliveries.  Without much poetry, I must say.... Sal's is the worst pizza I've ever tasted. It was so bad, I had to open a Yelp account just so I could set the story straight.  

I wish I could give it a positive review.  I just moved here, and am looking for my go-to pizza joint.  However, Sal's Pizza is as bad as frozen pizza. I was disappointed in the taste and texture of this pizza.  The crust was flavorless, and had that weird crispy/soggy thing.... overly crunchy outer crust, and soggy under the toppings.  No "bite, no bubbles.  BAD.  The sauce had too much oregano, not enough tomato flavor.  Too dark, not fresh tasting at all.  The toppings (I ordered caramelized onions, italian sausage and fresh ricotta cheese) were abundant enough, though there was not a lot of cheese on it.... kind of like a frozen pizza.

I also ried the garlic bread.  I liked that they offered free mozzarella cheese on the garlic bread - but i decided to have it without the cheese (assuming there would be plenty on the pizza).  The bread was greasy and very salty- as if it was flavored only with garlic salt.  

I've had a lot of pizza throughout the years.  Some delicious, some mediocre.  But i've never had a pizza from a Pizzeria that I wanted to throw away.  Sal's Pizza is the first.  Please, DO NOT WASTE YOUR MONEY.  This place stinks.

text: Beautiful property! I know I would not be able to ever afford to stay at the hotel because of the high prices for one night stay but I love stopping here when I am on the way to Santa Barbara. Just to stop and walk on their beach and property is totally worth it. I had the chance to try their ice cream shop Scoops. categories: Restaurants, American (New), Seafood, Steakhouses
text: A romantic culinary dream. Located up in the incredible Montecito hills, surrounded by wealth, class, and luxury, up in San Ysidro Ranch. Our anniversary was well spent last night, here at Stonehouse. The twinkle lights enveloped the patio as night fell creating a beautiful ambiance! Our waiter Adrian spent the evening taking care of us and was exceptionally knowledgable. The wine was paired perfectly with our dishes. We ordered the Diver Scallops as an appetizer which, if you love scallops, were breathtaking. Followed by the special for the evening, a Pan Seared Tuna, and I ordered the much anticipated Halibut dish, of which did not disappoint. The chocolate soufflé, a gooey delectable treat that, in my opinion, would be worth the visit all on its own. Will absolutely return, will remember this evening forever, and will stay at the hotel next time! Tip- get there early and walk the grounds, beautiful views!

text: Fantastic new coffee spot in Goleta.  Bigger and bolder than Goleta Coffee Company just not quite as much parking - BUT - there is plenty of free parking one block away at the Community West Bank.  It is worth the walk.  Great coffee, pastries -  I had a brioche sort of a roll filled with melted cheese and prosciutto, a good light breakfast item.   With a large comfortable space, hopefully they will add sandwiches soon.  If they would just put a sign about parking they would get much busier, maybe that's NOT a good idea, LOL. Lovely place to meet friends, or just relax for a minute with a really nice cuppa joe.  Oh wow, just noticed in another review that there is an outside area too?  Oyvay!

text:
Well, they do have the best price and they do perform the repair quickly.  However, the quality is a bit lacking.

I've had two windshields replaced by them on two different cars.  Both times, the replacement windshields fog up EASILY.  I'm talking, hop in the car on a misty day, take 3 breaths, and the windshield is fogged up.  Neither of the original windshields fogged up anywhere near this easily.

Also, their workmanship is not great.  The second windshield they replaced, they broke lots of plastic & rubber trim surrounding the windshield and left most of it loose for me to discover & fix myself.

text:
Nugget Bar & Grill

Decided to check this place out for dinner with the guys while we were out here in Goleta working on a project. 

The place is not huge and the parking, let's face it is even worse so plan accordingly. The wait was not long surprisingly even for a party of 4. 

They did happen to take a while to get our drink order and by the time the waiter came through we ordered our meal as well. Our food came out shockingly fast. 

Everything was picturesque to say the least, but full of flavor. Everything from burgers to fried chicken was cooked perfectly. 

The ambience seemed to say it was more of a local hangout spot for all ages and the place to be even on a Thursday night. Nonetheless it was a decent night and I would probably still come back again.

text:
My friend and I stopped by here on a whim to try someplace new. As soon as we pulled into the parking lot we noticed how lively the ambiance was outdoors, with a flat screen TV showing some soccer game and plenty of people having a good laugh.

We were pretty hungry so we started with half a dozen empanadas - Serrano, Hongos, Suiza, and a few other flavors. Each and every empanada we tried was a bite out of heaven, and the chimichurri sauce elevated the flavors to another level! We had to go back in to order more of the Serranos along with some tiramisu to wrap things up.

10/10 would recommend to anyone for a delicious brunch and top-notch coffee with a side of soccer!

text:
I have suffered with issues around anxiety, what I refer to as low grade depression, due to childhood trauma that I experienced.  In addition, in my mid fifties I started to notice a slight decline in mental acuity.

As a patient of Dr. Thompson, my experience has been one of profound healing, for myself and for my son.

After getting my brain map done, Dr Thompson and I were both able to see how my issues could improve through a combination of Neuro modulation while also having a talk therapy session.

Over the course of this past year my overall appreciation for life and general well being has increased, very little anxiety left, and little to no further depression.  Mental acuity has also improved, I feel like I can perform in my work like I did before, perhaps even better now.

My son had been labelled as ADD in elementary school.  He did struggle with school, but managed to do pretty well.  In college he was only able to pull solid grades from the film classes he took, otherwise he tended to tank.  He also had a very difficult time holding down a part time job.  

When my son met Dr Thompson, she determined that his brain profile did not match up with the typical profile of Adult ADD, but that he had a low voltage profile that could be improved upon.

In addition to the neuro modulation that he received, Dr Thompson worked with Adam and got him to find excitement in what he was most interested in and passionate about, which was and is screenwriting.

So the proof in the pudding here, is that my son enrolled in a screen writing BFA program four years ago in Los Angeles and in a few months he will graduate with that BFA! He also has had the same part time job for the last couple of years, running an escape room in Hollywood.  Huge progress!  

Any parent who has a child that they feel like they are really struggling to function, knows what a relief it is to see them start to thrive!

I am very proud of his accomplishments AND I am forever grateful to Dr. Thompson and her team, for finding the path that is allowing this young mans amazing creativity to be coming alive personally and professionally!

I have referred my friends to Dr Thompson, and have gotten rave reviews back from them as well.

We are very fortunate to have this clinic, Dr Thompson, Dr Dogris, and their staff here in our community!

text: It's the standard college spot that has happy hour deals, which are pretty good. We went for lunch on Friday and had 4 Greygoose and RedBulls, and one a la cart taco, our bill was $80. They charge double for the Goose and Bulls and don't give you a heads up. You get charged for the Greygoose drink, plus an extra $6 for redbull, but they use a new can each time, so you get to pay $10 to drink out of a plastic dixie cup that they used a jigger to pour. Stick to happy hour here, you'll need the 2 for 1, the drink's hardly have any alcohol.

Overall the service is friendly, and the work good. It's also kept clean and service is prompt.

text:
AVOID THIS PLACE AT ALL COSTS!
The worst so called BBQ we ever ate in our life!

We ordered take out and ordered 
a chicken dinner and a pulled pork sandwich. Both came with fries.
The chicken looked delicious but was so dry and flavorless we threw it out. 
The pork sandwich was served on a huge bun and it was barely two tablespoons of meat. 
Neither meats had any smoke flavor and the pork appeared boiled. 
The fries were supposed to be "freshly hand cut" but were nearly black and cold and had been cooked for some time.
NEVER GOING BACK!!

text:
Yes. Just yes.

I went to the public market with a group so that everyone could choose what they wanted to eat. Walking around, I ended up getting a beer at The Garden and my food from Empty Bowl. No regrets at all! 

I ended up ordering the Bangkok Street Noodle to go. Noodles with beef balls all soaking in this delicious spicy, savory and slightly sweet broth. It definitely hit the spot and was exactly what I was craving. 

I'd love to come back here and try out some of the other dishes on their menu. It was hard making a choice at all! Would definitely recommend this for anyone who likes Thai food done with a twist.

name: Scott Dewhirst, MD -  Sansum Clinic
categories: Psychics, Arts & Entertainment, Health & Medical, Psychiatrists, Supernatural Readings, Doctors
text: Dr. Dewhirst has worked closely with my other doctors to ensure my mental healthcare is very well taken care of for several years now. He has helped save my life more than once. When I moved out of town this year, he agreed to continue seeing me via telemedicine indefinitely, which was extremely important to me when deciding whether or not to move. If my insurance ever stops covering telehealth, I'll either pay out of pocket or drive to Santa Barbara (a 200-mile round trip) every few months for my appointments, despite that I live in LA surrounded by other psychiatrists. THAT is how excellent of a doctor he is. I always feel like he is on my side, an ally. He goes out of his way to take care of my mental health and is very supportive. He is also highly skilled with polypharmacy (managing multiple medications), which is necessary for me personally, while he also makes sure to never over-medicate. He always takes my opinions and feelings into consideration when making treatment decisions. Bonus: he is always on time! He is worth the very long waitlist.

text:
I really struggled with rating this restaurant. Torn between 2 stars and 3 stars, and ultimately chose to give it 2 stars because I think the quality of food weighs more than the service. 

Although the service was great (and I did like the free danishes they handed out in the beginning), sadly, the food was just terrible. I ordered the Sir Matthew pork patty, which was a HUGE disappointment considering it was supposed to be their speciality. The pork patty was meh, the sauce was overbearing and nothin special. And the worst part was the country potatoes. Oh man, they were soggy. Just terrible.

My husband ordered one of their breakfast croissant sandwich, and without taking a bite, I can assure that it didn't taste good. The sandwich came out totally smooshed. The delicate beauty of a croissant is the air, the fluffiness. They killed that. Plus, he asked for his egg to be over easy but it came out totally well done and over cooked.

I'm getting the feeling that most restaurants on State Street are bleh. Their level of service, however, is amazing.

I will never come back. Sorry!

categories: American (Traditional), Seafood, Sandwiches, Restaurants, Burgers, Breakfast & Brunch
text:
Much love for On The Alley, the food is delicious and relatively inexpensive! I would come here all the time when I was a college student for a quick meal. From burgers to breakfast burritos to Brophy Bros. classics, this casual harbor eatery has everything everybody will enjoy. Some of the menu items I've tried:

Fish & Chips - Always served piping hot and fresh out of the fryer. The batter is light and airy, with just enough crunch every bite. Perfectly flakey fish as well.

Clam Chowder - No need to travel to New England, Seattle, or Pismo! OTA's rendition is super creamy and savory. I'm not too crazy about their sourdough bread, but it satisfies a craving.

Crab Cake Burger - Probably one of their more inconsistent options, the crab cake patty can be a hit or miss when it comes to portion size.

Pulled Pork Sandwich - Generous amounts of slow-roasted pork, I know other places go ham when it comes to adding coleslaw. Thankfully that wasn't the case here.

OTA Burger - Your conventional burger but with a breakfast twist. Fried egg, avocado, and bacon make a very tasty combination.

Definitely a solid joint to visit if you're looking to eat by the water!

categories: Seafood, Bars, Wine Bars, American (New), Restaurants, French, Nightlife, Mexican
text:
Love this place.  It's right off of State Street and you might have some trouble parking during dinner time.  I had reservations for 8p and we were seated at 830p (we got there late - around 820p).  The ambiance is more laid back than the French restaurants up North - casual art, yellow walls, open view kitchen that looked like house kitchen, "Fly me to the moon" type of music, etc.  We liked that.

The savory foie gras is AMAZING.  it was on top of beet salad, spiced butternut puree, brioche crouton, and red wine jus.  It was a good sized portion and so buttery.  YUM!   My two friends like the Seared Diver Scallop Trio better.  It was these huge scallops in three ways - as salad, appetizer and then dinner.  We all agreed the salad scallop was the best.  

We had a bottle of the Point Conception chardonnay, which was really good with our appetizers.  By the time our entrees came around, I was full!  I had the duck, which was pretty awesome.  The Wagyu beef was pretty good and the friend that had the Ahi tuna with lemon mashed potatoes literally licked her plate clean.  

I would recommend this place to people of all ages (except kids) for any occasion or non-occasion.  Definitely would come back.  Our waiter (Eric), the host, the waitstaff, and the manager who would get on the chair to take our photos, were all gracious and very customer-service oriented.  The best I've seen in awhile.

One bad thing - they have retired the Blueberry cake for now (even though blueberries are in season).  I was really disappointed.  I don't recommend any desserts here.   Go somewhere else for dessert.

text: My husband, son & I come to this restaurant about once a week. They are a friendly consistent crew with a delicious food & wine selection that never disappoints. My husband loves the tortellini or rib eye with white beans. I love the ravioli with brown sage sauce & the rack of lamb. All of the salads and anti pasta are great. It's a welcoming neighborhood restaurant with a friendly intimate environment where I've never had a bad meal or bad service. It's well managed. The pizzas are really good too. Can't think of a negative thing to say about this consistently lovely & delicious restaurant!

categories: Breakfast & Brunch, Burgers, American (Traditional), American (New), Restaurants
text:
If anything, get the home fries (potatoes) for breakfast. They're the best that I have ever had; nicely seasoned throughout, good crisp. I wish I had the recipe. 
Busboys are not only professional but also friendly, happy and respectful. 
Every waitress has a good knowledge of the menu and can make appropriate recommendations should you want a substitution.  Coffee, water, and hot tea are checked on for refills. The cinnamon roll is about 6" wide so it's enough to split. 
Restaurant is very clean, as well as the restroom. 
Noise can be a little loud but when you have so many people coming in for one of the best breakfasts in town, it's expected. The tables in the back can be moved to accommodate larger parties. 
Very family-friendly, dogs okay outside. 
It's not a huge venue; just an unpretentious diner tucked into the corner of a strip mall on the north side of town.  I would have it no other way.  The food???????

Always excellent. Fresh ingredients. Nothing stale or turning. 

I write this review with a heavy heart because they deserve the accolades; however, I do not look forward to the day when I have to "wait to be seated ". 

God bless you, Farmer Boy!

text:
This is one of the few things I miss about Santa Barbara. I just don't know how to sum up my love for the Natty Cafe. Everything I've ever tried there has given me that good food high, but now, since I'm there like once a year or something, it's gotta be the Good Karma Burger. A tempeh patty with black beans and corn IN THE PATTY! IN THE PATTY, people. And Veganaise and soy cheese. It's so delicious. The smoothies are good, the appetizers (hummus, mmmm) are so good to share. And I just feel all clean and wonderful inside after eating there. 
It reminds of the Saturday war protests I used to go to every week when I lived there, and afterwards my hippy friends and I would scrounge up our change and go to the Natty. Ahhh, my introduction to Hippydom. Good memories.

categories: French, Cafes, Restaurants, Breakfast & Brunch, Food, Sandwiches, Bakeries
text:
I have been to Renaud's on several occasions and I have been very pleased with the food, pastries, and service up until my recent visit. 

We were on our way from Santa Maria and phoned in our order at 2:15pm to dine in at 2:30pm. We specifically requested to dine-in. Once we arrived, we paid the bill and our order was delivered to us in a to-go bag. Okay, fine. The person who took our order over the phone was a female, and the cashier who took our order was the only female in Renaud's. Therefore, one has to assume that the name on the receipt, Kiersten, is the one who received our phone order with instructions to serve the food for dine-in. Once we received our order in a bag, we sat down and unloaded the food on a table. We later found that we did not receive any butter and jam for the croissant. No biggie, I'll get up and ask for some. I ask Kiersten for some butter and jam, and she silently grabs some and hands them to me. I say thank you to her loud and clear, and she ignored me. It's one thing when someone doesn't want to be friendly, but when you are working with customers, I expect some sort of acknowledgement so that I, as a customer, can feel welcome for a small service that I paid for.

We ate our food, and it tasted mediocre which is way less than expected at this establishment. I don't know if our mood was lost, or we received the unwelcome service before the kitchen closed that resulted in poorly tasting food. How unfortunate. In addition to our experience, the other employees were two young males who were both chatting and laughing in a very loud manner as if no one was around. It was a Tuesday afternoon approaching 2:30pm and the kitchen was closing, I get it. However, Renaud's closes at 5pm. Overall, it was an unpleasant experience such that it seemed as though none of the workers wanted to work. Two stars for a one star experience because we had some great experiences in the past.
