text:
I was excited to try the Wildwood Kitchen but was ultimately disappointed. The restaurant has an appealing aesthetic but the acoustics are terrible. The noise was so loud that we had to shout to hold a conversation. BBQ can be very simple and tasty but, in this case, it was simple, overcooked, and bland. This was particularly annoying because the food was hyped by the wait staff as "really amazing" when it was decidedly not. The drinks were tasty but expensive so, when we got the bill, we felt that the overall price of the meal exceeded the quality. 

It seems something can be done about most of this - improve the food quality, humble the wait staff, for example - but the acoustics might be more tricky. I'd love these folks to succeed here in the "funk zone" of Santa Barbara, particularly because they've obviously invested a lot in putting it together, but I won't be back until I've heard about the improvements.

text:
2020 Peoples Choice (Independent) WINNNNNNNER of:
Best View
Best Bloody Mary
Best Sunday Brunch
Best Happy Hour (bester in the winter)
I agree on all points. Let's discuss.

The best barstool in town and my personal oasis for chill, visit with strangers/regulars and the stellar crew here while staring at the ocean.

Bars love to tout their Bloody Mary's. Here the hype is justified. Not a wet mess but a well rounded, spiced (not necessarily spicy cocktail). Filling and refreshing. Although not my go-to breakfast bevi here, they are worth ordering.

Sunday Brunch or any morning meal at the beach is a WINNER. The gang knows my order:  Step in the Right Direction and the Signature Breakfast. Whatever you choose, you'll always have the view. Which is nice.

Best Happy Hour is where you'll find me. The questions are 1. At what time and 2. For how long? The Boathouse Happy Hour follows the sun. Or more specifically the clock.
Daylight Savings Time (Summer): 3-6 Sunday through Thursday
Winter: 3-Close Sunday through Thursday a s some years a late night Friday option
They specials save you a couple bucks but more importantly is who this brings in. Locals, tourists, regulars, and first timers. I love it.
You'll know me from my signature glass of Chardonnay and fries. Those friend fries may be with the burger, local muscles, or on their own.

If you're a tourist, know there may be long lines to take in the view. For the locals/regulars, we know when to enjoy the patio all to ourselves but always happy to share. As long as you say "hi" when you see me.

Cheers

text: This shop is awesome. I had been walking/jogging along Morro Beach and seemed to have stepped into some tar sands created by Chevron over the past few decades. The smell on my shoes was hideous and I figured that I would need to trash them. However, on a lark we brought the shoes to this shop and the owner and repair team were able to get them cleaned up within an hour. I had tried everything to get the tar off my shoes but it didn't work. I'm not sure how they were able to work their magic, but the shoes are as good as new. I appreciate the fast service and reasonable price.

text: As recent transplants we've been on a vigorous and calorically enhanced mission to sample every restaurant in Santa Barbara. We now can declare definitively that STATE & FIG is the best burger. Boom. Start with a lovely brioche bun from a local bakery on De La Vina, the half pound burger is steak quality beef, cooked perfectly (my wife a well done; me a medium), with options that are complex but not silly as is often the case. I chose 'The Fig' with fig jam, grilled onions, arugula and blue cheese, just enough blend of tastes to enhance but not overwhelm the meat. The garlic fries are a revelation -- and if someone could figure a way to deliver them to me when I'm in my jammies watching Colbert eviscerate our clown in the White House, I'd call it heaven. Also noteworthy is a very genial and gregarious staff: in particular, Tracey, a fellow transplant from Pennsylvania who helped my wife figure out where to yoga, to massage, to pedicure and other verbs I'm making up. It's in that cozy courtyard at 1114 State and a great hang out. I don't eat much red meat so when I do, I do not want to waste my sinfulness on stinkiness! This is a better burger than any I've had in L.A. (maybe Pono Burger in Santa Monica is close). On we go exploring -- but this will become a regular stop!

text:
I tried this place just to try something new. I do have a place in Santa Barbara that I frequent at least once or twice a month, but since it was for New Years I thought, why not try something new? I ordered Kung Pao Chicken and Broccoli Beef for take out. They were good and the portion size was comparable to the portion size to my regular restaurant. Only other issue was I usually pay about $12 an entree and $4-5 for an appetizer and here it was about $16 for an entree and $8-10 for an appetizer. Also, the worst part was when I got home I realized there was no white rice in my order. I was shocked! I called a relative of mine who I knew had dined there very recently and I asked him and he did say they charge extra. FOR RICE! This is the only Chinese place that I can think of that does this. I checked their website listed in my Axxess book, and there is no mention (that I can see) that says there is an extra fee for white rice or that you need to order is separately etc. If I had at least seen a disclaimer or something I would have ordered it. I did not feel like driving all the way back to buy some since it was already late in the evening on New Years eve so my family and I just had the entrees by themselves, with no rice. 

Pros: Tasty, Good portion size
Cons: Need to pay extra for rice, overpriced

My suggestion to the owners would be to add something to their online menu that says "rice extra."

UPDATE:
Just realized there are TWO websites. One website listed in the Axxess book which is the one I used to look up my dishes. No mention of having to pay extra if you want rice. If you Google empress palace there is another website (probably an older one) where it says that rice is an extra $1 or something. Very confusing as I only look up whatever website is listed in the Axxess book. Like I mentioned in my review, update your website to reflect something that thousands of people see in the Axxess  book.

text:
Finally made it out to Angel Oak after hearing so many good things, and have to say - it did not disappoint! Some favorites were the beet salad, the lobster gnocchi, and the dry aged New York steak which was cooked to perfection. CiCi, the sommelier, picked out a delicious local Syrah for us to enjoy with our meal and Maureen, the manager, was so sweet and made sure our first visit was excellent in every way. 

Besides the amazing food and wonderful service, the restaurant itself is gorgeous and has spectacular ocean views all around. Highly recommend for a romantic date night or celebratory dinner with friends. Will definitely be returning!

text:
Nice tasting room but the pours were TINY.  We did enjoy several of the wines and purchased one.  We enjoyed the $15 tasting more than the $10. You could also purchase wines by the glass which is a nice feature.  There wasn't any complimentary cheese or charcuterie and there wasn't a theme to the tasting - I wish we had been there in February when Jessica C went there - that sounds like much more fun!  

Not that this really maters, but I really didn't like the labels on this wine.  They were so busy with so much going on - very distracting!  

There were at least two other tasting rooms within a 25 feet of Au Bon Climat, so if this isn't to your fancy, you can try either of those - they are on my To Do's for next time.

text: Off the beaten path, and SO DELICIOUS! We rolled into town late, and wanted a nice/light drink, and some delicious, vegetarian, and not heavy food, and Foxtail delivered! We had the fresh beet salad and roasted cauliflower to share for appetizers. Our mains were the Red Falafel Wrap and Veg Falafel Burger. Everything was spot on, and flavor! Their delicious Mediterranean food and lovely drink made for a great start to our visit. Thank you!

categories: Breweries, Food, Arts & Entertainment, Cideries, Wineries, Wine Tasting Room, Kombucha
text:
A fun little meadery/cidery/kombucha-y in Carpenteria! Yes, Google Maps took you to the right place. It's in the middle of a business park, but the interior makes you totally forget that fact!

We tried *almost* everything available, and boy we enjoyed it all!! Who knew mead could be good. Turns out, it's good!

Jun (green tea kombucha) was also a neat experience beyond the regular black tea kombucha we're used to. Not a favorite, but tasty!

The guy working behind the bar was extremely pleasant, hospitable, helpful, and informative. The entire vibe was laid back and chill (a welcomed mood after a few rambunctious cideries), with fun conversation had by all!

We got a bottle to go, and for sure will be back to refill it!

categories: Mexican, Restaurants
text:
6 loaded tacos, a drink, and a MUST-GET side of grilled onions and peppers made for a yummy lunch for two ($16~)! I am biased to tacos in San Diego though. We deliver fattier carne asada and adobada which takes the tacos to the next level! Although Lilly's tacos had lean meat and the adobada tacos didn't have the signature green sauce on them, they were delicious regardless because they were piled with protein. The salsa bar was nice with three different salsas and unlimited limes to your liking. The extra $1 for a plate of grilled onions and peppers is a must! They were sautéed perfectly and balanced out the salty and savory tacos nicely.

Overall these were pretty dang good! Very affordable prices, fast service, and did I mention they PILE it high with meat?! Will come back!

text: OMG!!!!  This is the place to pamper yourself!  I came here with my daughter to refresh, renew, rejuvenate myself. It was my spiritual and personal retreat. From start to finish they know how to make you feel pampered...and you are pampered. Firstly, the bell hops will handle your trip items for your room, drive your car to the garage, unload and put away your things in your room.  The rooms are, not just daily refreshed and changed, but changed in between the daily change. It seems they cater to your activity and if you leave your room for the day, they make sure you come back to a clean, freshly made up rooms. New, clean towels. Your property nicely folded and organized and placed neatly away. They even rolled my phone and computer cords and placed them neatly on the desk next to my bed where I had them. Our room had fireplace and I asked for private bungalow. Deep bathtub, robes daily. House slippers daily. Espresso machine. Big mirrored closet space which is 4-doored. Even their ashtray is a metal flower work of art. But I guess that's expected for 5-star place. They really strive to make their facility on all levels a 5-star status. We had an 80 min body treatment which was amazing!  Showers, slippers, own lockers key coded, brush, shampoo, rainfall shower head showers plus smaller shower head, shower robe, plenty of towels, teas, waters, champagne...normal things for this place. They have valet service to the nearby town and pickup just phone call away. Amazing from start to finish. Wer coming back, I believe, to make this our annual retreat...or maybe our bi- or tri-annual retreat. Lol.

name: Luxury Nails
attributes: {'BusinessParking': "{'garage': False, 'street': True, 'validated': False, 'lot': False, 'valet': False}", 'BikeParking': 'True', 'RestaurantsPriceRange2': '2', 'ByAppointmentOnly': 'False', 'BusinessAcceptsCreditCards': 'True'}
categories: Nail Salons, Beauty & Spas
text:
As a mom to a toddler, it's hard for me to get out and have my nails done - and I WISH I'd gone somewhere else today.  The location was convenient to my house though, so I thought I'd give it a try. Bad decision.  First of all, they really nickel-and-dime you.  Their basic spa pedicure is $25 and basic mani is $12.  They sit you down in the chair and immediately start in with how dry your nails are and how you NEED the next step up (read:more expensive) treatment.  The ladies were very pushy about it, and it took four attempts before they finally accepted a "no, thank you".  

That was just the first 30 seconds.

Throughout the entire mani-pedi, more pushy offers.  While she's massaging my calves, "you want five minutes more?"  She asked this THREE times.  While she's doing my toes, "you want expanded pedi? You NEED it.  Only $10 more".  

It is $5 extra to have a "hot oil treatment" for your fingers.  This fancy treatment (which apparently I NEEDED) consisted of a bowl of hot lotion.  Same stuff, just warm.  I paid extra for that?

I needed my nails buffed, not polished.  You guessed it - $5 more.  After all was said and done, I paid $47 for a crap job (messy toes and unfinished cuticles on hands, plus a half-ass buff job) and unpleasant, pushy atmosphere.

But wait, there's more!  I handed the lady my card and she said the total was "$47.... how much you want to put on the card?"

As you may have guessed, I was NOT about to leave a tip.  I said, "$47 is fine."

She said again, as if I hadn't heard her, "Total $47.  How much you want on the card?"   

Unreal.  Luxury Nails, the only luxury you offer is the ability to walk out the door and never come back.

text: I got talking with the owner and he told me that he spent his apprenticeship learning from my side of the world in Western Australia. And then he got me a glass of their sparkling Shiraz (aka FIZZ) which blew my mind. Not only does this place have cool knowledgable pourers. But the style of this place truly is unique. Maintaining a unique feel right down next to the beach it resides in a gutted out dive shop that now has more of a feeling of a cali/ NY remodeled studio warehouse. The curation of the space is brilliantly don with amazing wine bottle chandeliers and filing cabinet wine holders. They have wine on tap which you can come and fill up growlers whenever you need and the design from the T-shirts to the wine bottles is so engaging and fresh. I went through their catalogue and every year they have outperformed on the designs. I even love the name of their club - Club Awesome. Municipal Winemakers comes with the highest recommendation - you will not be disappointed. Especially with The FIZZZZZZZZZZZZZZZ!!!!

categories: Italian, Restaurants
text:
With my fiance and I both feeling under the weather but a little chicken-souped-out, we couldn't think of a better food idea than a fresh plate of steaming pasta.  But where to go?  None of the half-dozen Italian places we had been to in the area seemed appealing.  On to Trattoria Vittoria!

Upon walking in, the restaurant gave off a warm, friendly, neighborhood vibe with tables nestled closely together and bright copper pans hanging on the walls.  The tv at the bar was playing an old Jimmy Stewart movie which (though un-bar-like) seemed to fit the place just fine.  

We ordered some basics: calamari fritti to start, and then two of the house-made pastas--lasagna and tagliatelle with mushrooms.  The calamari was crisp, tender, and flavorful.  There was almost no need to add lemon or the bright, fresh, clean tomato sauce accompaniment.  Which brings me to my next point, as the tomato sauce is what makes an Italian restaurant for me.  Their sauce actually tastes like distilled tomatoes--shocking, but true!  No masking with random dried herbs, pre-processed garlic, or copious amounts of other veggies.  Tastes like tomatoes.  Good deal.  I approve.  The lasagna was great--layers of flat house-made pasta and ground meat (unctuous mouthfeel--veal, perhaps?) flavored subtly with what I think was nutmeg and topped with the awesome aforementioned tomato sauce.  The tagliatelle was also lovely; there is something timeless and comforting about the luxury of mushrooms, cream, and fresh pasta.  Ahh...  

Yes, we both felt better after the meal, not just because it eased the symptoms of our colds, but also because we now have a new go-to Italian restaurant in the area--definitely cause to celebrate!

text:
Da wife and I were in Goleta and of course I checked yelp out for a seafood joint and Nikka came up.  The reviews looked good enough to give it a go.

Am glad we did.  My wife ordered the squid and chips and I got the fish and chips.  Of course we shared.  I tasted the fish and it was moist and flaky, just amazing.  I ate mine without any sauce or vinegar.  Da wife's squid was just okay, a bit too much batter, but it was good.

The chipotle sauce, we left it for dead.  It kind of tastes like a tartar sauce mixed with bbq sauce.  Had to ask for cocktail sauce which they didn't seem to have, then one of the guys in the back said he would bring it out.  Now cocktail sauce is nothing but ketchup and horseradish.  They should always have it.

The people were great, service excellent and the price was really good.

Like one of the reviews stated, you have to go to the sushi joint a few doors down for the restrooms.  No big deal, they didn't care and they were clean.

There were a lot of items on the menu, if we wind up back in Goleta we're going to be checking them out too!

name: Miracle At The Funk Zone
categories: Restaurants, Pop-Up Restaurants, Bars, Cocktail Bars, Local Flavor, Nightlife
text:
Honestly a little disappointed. I wanted to give this place a second shot before leaving a review, and both experiences were the same. 

I came on opening weekend to celebrate with a relative and the staff did not have it together. I had reached out prior to our reservation to inquire about special accommodations for a birthday, then another time for a reservation for a larger group, and no response was ever given. Not only that, but it seemed like the staff needed some more time to get their bearings straight prior to opening, everyone seemed a little disoriented and under-trained for the event.

I spoke with the manager during my first visit to secure a reservation for a larger group of us for a few weeks later, and after some time, he was able to make it work and assured us that our reservation would be inside the bar. Fast forward to the date of that large reservation, we were told we had to sit outside (do not recommend), and after some back and forth and a 15 minute wait, they were able to sit us inside, only then for us to have to wait another 20 minutes to get our drinks.

I will say, the wait staff were very nice and the decor is great! This is definitely a cool pop up, just be prepared. 

TL;DR: the wait staff were very nice, the bar staff were pretty slow, and the music from the bar adjacent to Miracle/Pearl plays incredibly loud music on the weekends, plus half of the Christmas light display lights didn't work, so don't sit outside.

categories: Indian, Food, Restaurants, Bubble Tea, Pakistani, Fast Food
text:
I'm not the best judge of Indian food and I know there can be more to improved upon for this place, but it deserves 5/5 stars in my eyes due the prices, the sizes, and the accessibility.

I had the chicken tikka masala, chicken curry, the samosas, and the Mango Lassi. The rice bowl is under $7 and fills you up well. While my chicken curry was somewhat watery at the end and the rice portion is definitely larger than the entree, it filled me up really well and I was satisfied. The curry had a mild spice to it. The chicken tikka masala was good, too.

The mango lassi was so big! It was $4, so we were having second doubts, but the size was decent and it tastes good! As for the samosas, they're ENORMOUS. And they're $2. The sauces are located next to the straws by the menu. One fills me up right away.

The store isn't the cleanest and I see more people do take-out than dine-in, but Naan Stop is a decent place for an Indian food fix and when in IV, my standards become pretty low. Check it out!

text:
Yelp never fails to come through for dinner suggestions.  Road trip from NorCal to SoCal along 101, and searched best Chinese restaurants in Santa Barbara.  We chose Stone Age, and so glad we did!  
We got the vegetable spring rolls for an appetizer and then ordered the beef fried rice and noodles with chicken.  Everything was great.  Brought to the table immediately after being plated.  Nice treat to have food arrive in front of you and actually seeing steam coming off the food on your plate.  Spring rolls were crisp and non greasy.  Plum
Sauce good, without a heavy sugar taste.  Rice and noodles fantastic.  Only thing I would change is maybe a thicker noodle.
Daughter ordered a rose milk tea to go.  I took a sip of it and was pleasantly surprised at how good it was as I usually do not like milk tea.  
We do not go this way often, but will definitely keep in mind if we pass this way again!

name: Avania Inn of Santa Barbara
attributes: {'RestaurantsPriceRange2': '2', 'BusinessAcceptsCreditCards': 'True', 'WiFi': "u'free'"}
categories: Resorts, Hotels & Travel, Hotels, Event Planning & Services
text: My parents are retired and have a pretty strict budget, which is why they were so excited to find the rates of Avania Inn so affordable. However, after being at the hotel for one night they were informed the power was going to be turned off for the entire second evening of their stay. The hotel gave them a very small "discount" on the room for the second night and 2 candles that barely provided enough light to move around the room. My dad is 80 years old and has Parkinson's Disease and due to the immense amount of energy it takes to get around my mom thought it was best to just stay put since changing hotels would be so difficult for my dad. Had I not been 6 hours away I would have driven there, packed them up and found them a hotel that was not going to overcharge them to stay in a dark room with no electricity. My parents take one vacation a year and Avania managed to put a damper on it. When I was attending college in Santa Barbara my parents would stay at this hotel, but it was under different ownership. Some things are beyond the control of the hotel (I imagine they could not turn the power on if they wanted to), but it would have been kind of the hotel staff to offer to help identify and/or move to a new hotel for the evening. One would think that upon seeing a couple that clearly has limited mobility they would offer some extra support, or at least more than 2 candles to ensure that my dad could see on his way from his bed to the bathroom in the middle of the night!

name: Explore Wines Tour
attributes: {'BusinessAcceptsCreditCards': 'True', 'RestaurantsPriceRange2': '2', 'BusinessParking': "{'garage': False, 'street': False, 'validated': False, 'lot': False, 'valet': False}", 'BikeParking': 'False', 'ByAppointmentOnly': 'True', 'WiFi': "u'free'", 'GoodForKids': 'False'}
categories: Tours, Arts & Entertainment, Transportation, Wineries, Hotels & Travel, Wine Tours, Food, Limos
text:
Lisa was fabulous from the minute she pulled up in her shiny sprinter. I highly recommend her services as a guide. She was terrific!

Warm, welcoming & enthusiastic, she immediately started sharing her knowledge of wine in California and a few tid bits about the area. I lapped it up- I'm a history junky though, but she offers a disclaimer- she'll only tell you as much or as little as you're interested in learning. It's the Goldilocks rule- I'm telling you, Lisa is a pro at this and a consummate professional. 

My husband & I were discerning before booking this adventure. Having tasted quite regularly in Los Olivos and other parts of Santa Ynez, we wanted to pick a guide more knowledge than us who could bring us to places we hadn't ventured. We had guests in town who had never experienced the area so we also wanted to be sure they had a banner experience. We called multiple vendors rated through yelp, and after interviewing Lisa, felt as though we'd be in great hands. 
 
Our itinerary would be 3 wineries, all with outstanding wines- each with a distinct location, ambiance and style. The first would be more educational, the 2nd more experiential, the 3rd more commercial tasting room, & the 4th a bonus, adventure!

I don't want to spoil the fun & name the wineries, or betray Lisa's agenda but I can say this much- we had some of the best wines I've ever tasted. That includes tasting in the multiple regions of California. I was floored by these jammie syrahs. They were incredible! 

Also a fact- we purchased wine at each location we went to. They were that good. 

Lisa is incredibly adept at putting together itineraries based on your goals. We wanted a mix- starting with an educational, off the main strip location. She delivered a beautiful spot with a magnanimous owner. 
Our next location brought us to a beautiful setting where we were able to off-road tour through the grapes. It was so fun! Bucket list - box checked. 
Our 3rd location was a place I've driven by time & time again but never stopped at. I was so happy to be introduced to this winery. Their wines were delectable! 
Our last location featured my favorite vitner of the day. A young, entrepreneurial wine maker getting his footing but who has all the markings for success. Meaning- killer vino. 

See Lisa Stoll with explorer wines tour. Her chariot, a large black Mercedes sprinter is cool & comfortable interlude between tastings & she is as friendly as the day is long.

text:
I normally come on Yelp just to look at reviews beforehand so I know who to make an appointment with (or at least, who to avoid). I saw a good number of people complementing Maggie so I made an appointment for brow threading with her. I can see why so many people had nice things to say about her!

Normally when I get my brows done they do them really fast and I get a brief look in the mirror and then I head out. Now that I'm home and examining them even more, I can say this is the best my brows have looked after an appointment!

name: R J Carroll and Sons Plumbing
attributes: {'ByAppointmentOnly': 'True', 'BusinessAcceptsCreditCards': 'True'}
categories: Home Services, Plumbing
text:
Paid $860.50 to stop a toilet from leaking. My husband was the one who finally fixed it.

I called specifically about the following matters: one toilet backing up too frequently, another toilet leaking, and a sink faucet leaking. While there, the plumber did something which was supposed to help stop the toilet from stopping up. He told us he could not fix the sink without a replacing a valve which he didn't have. Did he go get this valve and come back? NO. He turned down the water pressure and said it would help. He looked at the second toilet which was leaking, simply told my husband how he should go about fixing it, and he left. BTW, I was the client that made the call, not the man in my house. But instead of checking in with the CLIENT, which was me, he just left. And the toilet KEPT overflowing after his visit. THANKS FOR This USELESS visit cost me $212 --- what a huge waste of my money and time.

I called AGAIN hoping to get all the things fixed that I had originally called your company for, given that first plumber had fixed NOTHING. This time second plumber came. He did actually stop the toilets from overflowing - which was his only success. He tried to stop the other toilet from leaking by adding a second seal, which failed. GUESS WHAT? My husband watched a YouTube video, paid $20 for a kit to rebuilt the whole interior (all in 30 minutes, including the video); now it works perfectly, with no leaking at all!
Both plumbers told me I needed to BUY a new toilet, and the second one was only too happy to coordinate and do that work for me. Oh, and my SINK faucet now leaks faster than EVER. Then second plumber told us the water pressure was too high, and turned it down (which had been turned up by first plumber the previous week - seriously?). Then, while I was trying to work on my computer (you know, for my job), he spent nearly 30 minutes trying to upsell me on new toilets and a new sink/vanity and how skilled and happy he would be do the work for me. Yes, he was quite a talker. I was billed for those 30 minutes. They charged me $50 to listen to him try and sell me things I did not want or need.

I called the office manager, explaining this situation, she told me she would talk to "someone" and get back to me. NOPE, no one reached out to me.  I still received bills that were at the full, original price in the original statements. I was a customer for 12 years.

text:
the calle real kyles has a serious quality control problem, and this is coming from a former food service manager. 

4 out of the past 5 times coming to this location they have forgotten to put all of the ingredients in my order, and each time the lettuce was old and brown. This last time i asked they made sure to put avacado and cheese as they forget often. I got home to find they just cut an avacado in half and plopped it on top without slicing it or taking the skin off. Wtf? Not only that the cheese was old and hard. Disgusting. 

Think twice about getting a salad or takeout from this location...

text:
I was only a member here for a limited time this summer, but I would highly recommend this gym to anyone looking to get in a serious workout.  

I really enjoyed that most of the time at the gym, I had the place to myself. I never had to wait for specific machines or share space because of this.  There are not a ton of cardio equipment (so if that's your thing, you may want to go elsewhere), but the gym is great if you want to lift and work on improving your strength. I would run there, work out for 45 minutes or so, then run home. It was perfect and quiet and had everything I wanted out of a gym.  

I really enjoyed my time there and if I were to recommend a gym to someone who wants to get in a great workout, this place would be it.  August, the owner, was very friendly and accommodating too. And the trainers at the gym took their time to welcome me to the gym and introduce themselves too.

text:
Art and I had our first date night since Valentines Day.. Highly recommend the Rincon Beach Bar in Carpinteria!! Marc and his team created a romantic, COVID safe, beautiful, gastronomic paradise!! We could hear the waves of the ocean in the background. Each table was 9 feet apart everyone wore masks and all of the ordering is contactless, you order from your phone! We had so much yummy food: Watermelon Wave, and Surfers Lemonade Cocktails paired with Seared Shrimp, Chicken flautas, Hawaiian Ahi poke, Nashville Hot chicken over a homemade biscuit and ended it with House Made Churro bites!! Even brought some Churros home for the kids!
It was such an amazing restaurant experience the beauty of the venue, the incredible food and knowing Marc and his team took excellent care to follow and exceed Covid requirements! Thank you Marc!!

name: The Presidio Hotel
attributes: {'BusinessAcceptsCreditCards': 'True', 'RestaurantsPriceRange2': '2', 'WiFi': "u'free'"}
categories: Hotels & Travel, Hotels, Event Planning & Services
text:
I love it here. The hipster folks who run it are really nice and had great information about where to eat, where to shop, interesting things to do, and even had some recommendation for thrift store hunting! 

The room looked like it was straight out of ReadyMade magazine -- very DIY. The lounge chairs on the deck and music piped though an outdoor speaker system (great choons by the the likes of DJ Shadow, Don Air, etc.) were also a nice touch. Breakfast was even part of the deal -- fruit, scones, muffins, coffee, etc. The location was excellent -=- close to the downtown area, but no too close) and the free bikes so you could pedal around town and down the the beach were a fantastic amenity. 

The only thing that was sort of a bummer was that the hip veneer kinda vanished when I saw the stained old bathtub, which gave me a hint that this probably used to be an old Best Western that had been bought and upgraded with some cool cosmetic upgrades. 

If you're ok with a bathtub that looks like it's been much used (which I am, hey I'm from San Francisco), you'll dig this place -- a lot.

text: When I need a quick fix of lux, I drop into Santa Barbara's Cabana Home. (And I live in LA!) This unbearably chic interior design studio and gallery always offers a warm welcome, room vignettes that inspire and local yet, nationally vaunted artists. Seriously, I never leave without a design book or at least an intoxicating candle! Owners Caroline Thompson and Steve Thompson are always on hand for guidance either in their gallery or have even come to my home when I was having a design meltdown. Plus, they are one of the original Funk Zone settlers, so there's always a secondary raison d'être to walk the 'hood for a quick coffee or better yet... wine tasting.  The best!

text:
Super excited to get a pho restaurant in Carpinteria but wasn't wowed as I was hoping I would be. I guess I shouldn't have had such high hopes.

This is a fast casual spot where you order first and they bring their food to you. Right away I noticed their prices were definitely higher than expected, even for higher end pho restaurants. They seem to be charging what the Carpinteria market will bear. 

Our table was not wiped down upon sitting but it was busy at lunch and their front of the house staff was young / new to the menu. 

Spring rolls were 2 for $5 and on the small side. A large house special bowl of pho (P1) was $11.50 (small was $1 cheaper @ $10.50). The broth was decent but not spectacular. There was a pretty generous portion of meat but the eye-round and/or flank was a little on the chewier side. Would have preferred quality over quantity. Petite portions of basil, sprouts, and jalapeno (3 little slices).

Co-workers ordered various broken rice dishes and tofu bowls and weren't impressed or disappointed either.

Bottom line - Phoevermore didn't deliver on quality and value that I expect from a good pho restaurant. If they dropped their prices by a few more bucks it would be a much better and more frequented spot. I'll come back again and probably try a bowl of the small rare-beef pho (P2) for $9.50.

text:
"The world is little, people are little, human life is little. There is only one big thing -- desire." 
― Willa Cather, The Song of the Lark

The area around the Santa Barbara train station has grown exponentially over the last few years.  Now there are a plethora of restaurants, wineries, shops whereas before there was just the original Lilly's Tacos (Still the best taco experience I've ever had).  I discovered both the Spanish restaurant and The Lark last year and decided to try The Lark once again before another SB Bowl concert. While last year I would have given it 5 stars, this year the experience was not quite that magnificent so I will give it 4 stars.  

A plus of course is free valet parking.  Given lack of parking in area, that starts the meal off right.  The restaurant includes both indoor and outdoor seating, both times we sat outside. Reservations available through Open Table. 

We were seated on recent visit next to Lucky Penny's patio and that creates a weirdness of hearing two outdoor music playlists. These two places really should coordinate.  It definitely detracts from the experience.  

Service was solid but not overly friendly.  And some gaps by not offering us the bread course, disappearing for long stretches.  But those are minor irritants.  

As for the food, not as wonderful as last year.  The cheese board was not as impressive, crackers not as good as the bread.  Strawberry jam was best part.  

The salad my dining companion ordered this year was just okay however the charred octopus was out of this world good. The Santa Barbara Gruner Veltliner we started with was lovely, the Santa Ynez Cabernet was also nice but lacking a bit body. They also gave us a taste of the Lo-Fi Gamay but it was too unsubstantial to consider ordering.  
So five star visit last year, 3.5 stars this year.  I will call it a 4 star.  

Recommended, but pricey especially with wine.  I think there is better value elsewhere and the competing music ambiance lowers value of outside seating.

text:
The 3 sentence review: This place is a perfect breakfast/brunch place! You need to treaty yo' self and start with the beignets because they are so delicious. The fried chicken benedict is super yummy and filling so I'd recommend sharing this one, unless you are are super super hungry. 

ATMOSPHERE: There's a free parking lot. The servers are super friendly. The only reason I'm not giving this place a 5 star is because the service was a little slow and it wasn't very crowded when my friend and i went. Granted, we did go about 40 minutes before closing so they were probably busy closing up shop.

BEIGNETS: Can you say beign-yay? These little puffy pastries really hit the spot and gave me that extra boost of sugary energy I needed. They are coated in powdered sugar and they give you maple syrup on the side. So I suggest getting these for the table to share and then getting something more savory, like...

THE FRIED CHICKEN BENEDICT: The second I saw this on the menu I knew I was going to get it. It's 2 fried chicken breasts resting on biscuits and smothered with gravy. Plus, you get a side. I highly recommend the home fries. Bon appetite!

text:
We came upon this place while looking for a nice dinner while walking around State Street.  The atmosphere is great, with a nice outdoor patio, and a very talented guitarist who had a very eclectic playlist.
The food was great, and the portions huge.  The only problem was the service.
Our waiter seemed like he didn't want to be there.  While asking him questions about the menu he seemed entirely indifferent, either unable or unwilling to answer our questions or offering any recommendations.  I ended up explaining the dishes to my girlfriend, as the waiter was of no help.
On top of that it took forever to get our drinks.  We asked for straws, but never got them.  When we were finished and asked for our check he sat and talked with the other staff for 5-10 minutes with our check in his hands before dropping it.
I'm giving it 4 stars b/c a bad waiter shouldn't be indicative of a place as a whole, but as this was my first time here, it may be.  Just something to keep in mind.

text: The fish here is very fresh.  If you like ahi tuna(fresh raw tuna steak) for poke bowls or just eating w/ rice or lightly grilled, this is the place to pick that up.  I am so so sorry I don't remember the type I purchased because they sell two types of raw tuna but I believe they just have one AHI which is what I purchased.  It cuts like butter and tastes like they caught it moments before selling to you.  Yes this is more expensive than grocery stores but grocery store tuna is normally AWFUL, and if you are a regular consumer of sushi and raw fish you know the fish market is the way to go and this place is FRESH. Staff is helpful with meal planning and do their best to provide sauces and extras with large purchases, with approval from managers.  Been here 4-5 times and will continue to eat here when I can afford it!  The the salmon roe too, that stuff is better than I've had it anywhere.

text:
The manager working [June 27th, 2016] was extremely unreasonable. Whoever took our order did so like a pro - he asked us how many wings we wanted, what sauce, etc. My girlfriend and I ordered it on Speaker Mode so we both heard him take down our order perfectly. 

Then the delivery guy came. AWESOME guy, assistant manager he said. He delivered our order just because there was short staff, thank you. The problem came when they forgot the wings. The Assistant Manager told me "sorry about that, call them up and tell them to come back/give you credit". That's when I met the manager :)))) an extremely unreasonable lady. She said because "it would be a waste of money to send you out wings since it doesn't show on your receipt". Waste of money? I've never heard of such a customer-losing statement in my life!  To whoever is reading this, trust me..... we ordered those wings and told them every single detail about them (8 pieces, extra sauce, ranch etc.) ---- it sucked. But I learned something..... The absence of wings can ruin an entire meal. How cool huh? .... It's alright though, we aren't actually that mad. 

We just know what sharing the truth can do and I don't want any young lad like myself to have to go wingless on a monday night. 

- Nik Koyama 
You won't see me again... #Rustys

name: Canzelle Alpacas
attributes: {'ByAppointmentOnly': 'True', 'DogsAllowed': 'False', 'GoodForKids': 'True', 'WiFi': "u'no'"}
categories: Arts & Entertainment, Farms
text:
There is no activity that compares to the amazing experience of being surrounded by beautiful, furry creatures on an ocean view property in the magnificent sunshine of Carpinteria, CA. Literally, nothing like it. 

Canzelle Alpacas is a ranch owned and run by the wonderful Carol Anne who invites tour groups and charity events into her private space to learn about, love and embrace alpacas, llamas, water buffalo, sheep, and doggos. She has a different program she runs for each group but the basis of it all is enjoying these wonderful animals, taking adorable one-of-a-kind pictures with them, and learning about where they come from, what their fur is used for, what tricks they can learn, and so on. 

The property itself is gorgeous ranch located right off of Foothill Rd not 5 minutes from downtown Carp. It is a little difficult to find the first time around but if you use Apple Maps (not Google, it sends you to the wrong location) and/or follow the directions she has listed on her website it is not a long ride at all. Just remember to look out for the house number (4036) when on Foothill AND when driving up the dirt path and wondering where to turn. 

I am not certain how many alpacas exactly are on the property but I would definitely say more than enough to excite you and feel surrounded by silly love. Carol Anne is so smart and can passionately tell you anything you'd like to know about them, as well. It is a wonderfully upbeat time outside in beautiful nature and will create photographs and memories you will cherish forever. 

Would recommend a visit to anyone and everyone, but if you need a specific reason, maybe for Christmas card pictures, hosting a charity event, looking for something unique while visiting town rather than the usual touristy go-to's, and silly date ideas with a Wow-factor.

text: I have never heard a front desk person say no so many times in my life.   What happened to old school hospitality?  My husband & I arrived here at 8:45 from a 5.5 hour drive from SF.  We were looking forward to taking a soak in the hot-tub....this thought got us through multiple bouts of holiday traffic.  During check in I had a couple basic questions.  The first being, where is the hot-tub and what are the hours?    The front desk person promptly said with a smile " we don't have one, sorry".  I let him know that there are multiple images on google showing a hot tub & that was an amenity we were really looking forward to.  He replied with a smiley, "sorry".  I was super bummed to say the least, but still trying to stay positive.  I then asked if they had any rooms with regular tubs inside, the front t desk person said, "yes, let me see" followed by a really quick,"nope -sorry" (another big smile).  I'm pretty mellow, but worked in hospitality in the past & thought his behavior was becoming cocky and just not very hospitable.  While handing me my room key he said "so you'll be in the bottom floor..." I had to stop him there.... "bottom floor?  It would be really nice if you had something on a higher level....do you?"  "Let me check -No Sorry!".  I then asked if I were to find another room nearby that had a hot -tub, would I be able to cancel this room since that was one of the main reasons I booked here..... his reply: "No Sorry your past your 24 hour cancellation policy".  I feel like I'm stuck in prison and being charged for it monetarily.  What is happening in hospitality?

categories: American (Traditional), American (New), French, Restaurants
text:
Had a date night at Stella Mare's after hearing lots about it. It's quite the Santa Barbara/Montecito institution. 

PROS: 
Gorgeous venue! An old Victorian mansion with oodles of charm, if you like the French country chic vibe. 

Great selection of dishes. We had a salad (the endive, apple and blue cheese) and it was delicious. Good French onion soup, and we enjoyed the seared fois gras (though not as much the mushroom accompaniment with which it came). 

In general, good service (see my caveat below with our wine not arriving in time). 

Live music! So fun. It got festive but not overly loud. 

CONS:
A little disappointed in one of our dishes. We got the rack of lamb with roasted potatoes. Lamb was delicious but definitely not rare or medium rare - it was on its way to well done. Potatoes tasted like they had been roasted the day before, and then just warmed up in some way. They had that slightly grainy texture, and were a little tough. Definitely not fresh roasted, which is what I would expect for a $30 entree. 

Even though we ordered two glasses of wine with our entrees, they didn't arrive. When they did, they were comped due to the wait (which we very much appreciated). 

Due to those two things, I have to take off two stars. Rack of lamb can be tricky to cook, but if it's on the menu, you better do it right! And, we didn't send it back because it was still good and not inedible - it was just too well-done.

text:
I've stayed at the Bacara plenty of times but never ate at this place, only walked by as it looked kind of stuffy. This time, I decided to give it a go with a few friends. I'd like to start with saying that the view at this place is phenomenal. If you can sit on the patio, definitely do. Even if its chilly, they have space heaters.

We tried a few starters, including the macaroni and cheese which was sooo goooey and delicious! We also had the foi gras torchon and some other salad with giant tomatoes. All delicious. For main meals we got the pan seared scallops and the abalone. The abalone rainbow chard was seriously amazing that two of us almost licked our plates clean. They serve it with a pasta which was perfect, you could cut right through it with a fork. Plus you get to keep the shells when you're done and who doesnt love that! The scallops were also declicious but I have to say the other meal was much better. We finished off the meal with a desert. We ordered the candy bar because the waiter said it was unique and their signature meal. Wellll, it was ok but was so overly sweet it was almost like eating a bunch of candy bars. It was almost too much to where we all 3 wished we had gotten the cobbler instead. They accidentaly brought a cobbler to our table and set it up, then when we said we only ordered one they took it away, which I also hope they didnt serve to anyone else because thats illegal. They wouldn't let it stay at our table so I guess instead of comping it to us because they messed up, they'd rather throw it away. The server who also took it away was saying snarky remarks as he walked off which rubbed us the wrong way. He was kind of a dick but whatever.

The only downside was the rudest old lady I've ever witnessed who was at the table behind us. The didnt have any silverwear and took it upon herself to yell outloud at the waitress to get it together. She also sent her food back and was throwing fits. Luckily the staff held it together nicely as I would have punched her in the throat. But once she had food in her and shut up, it was back to a wonderful time.

All in all if you're looking for great quality meal with no budget in mind, I'd give it a shot. The beautiful views and friendly staff (minus the dessert douchebag) are worth the experience.

name: Salt Cave Santa Barbara
attributes: {'RestaurantsPriceRange2': '2', 'ByAppointmentOnly': 'False', 'BikeParking': 'True', 'BusinessAcceptsCreditCards': 'True', 'BusinessParking': "{'garage': True, 'street': True, 'validated': False, 'lot': False, 'valet': False}", 'NoiseLevel': "u'quiet'", 'AcceptsInsurance': 'False', 'DogsAllowed': 'False', 'WheelchairAccessible': 'True', 'WiFi': "u'free'", 'BusinessAcceptsBitcoin': 'False'}
categories: Cosmetics & Beauty Supply, Massage Therapy, Shopping, Massage, Beauty & Spas, Halotherapy, Health & Medical, Day Spas
text:
It's hard to not get into "the zone" once you come downstairs to the Salt Cave. You automatically feel like everything around has a healing power, that the goodies they sell must do your skin good, and the salt particles you walk on maybe help you release what no longer serves you. 
My husband and I had ordered a couple massage which included the salt save session. Once we signed in, we were escorted to the waiting area. Here your experience begins. The floor is filled with salad particles so you must remove your shoes before entering. They provide you with some tea and water as you wait for your masseuse to come get you.
Our masseuses came and lead us to the room where we would receive our couples massage. Here too the floor was filled with salt, the walls were what looked like big salt blocks, and the ceiling was also filled with big salt pieces. The room had relaxing music playing and it was nice and dim and the relaxing and fit for a relaxing session. 
My masseuse was very sweet and good at what she does. After asking a few questions, she suggested I do the Swedish massage. My massage began in a nice warm massage bed with nicely scented essential oils that helped you drift into meditation mode. After about 25 min into my massage there was a loud noise that disturbed the peace. It sounded like running water like someone showering or flushing the toilet from upstairs (since the cave is basically in the basement). I lifted my head to see what it was, but from the reaction of the ladies giving the massage, I realized it wasn't something out of the ordinary. Again, as I tried to get zone out the noise came back. This happened 3 times in the one hour that I was getting my massage. Although, my massage was very relaxing because the masseuse was great, the experience was not the best. For 300$ I would not expect to run into such problems. It was very irritating and hard to get the peace and quiet we paid for.
After the massage, they gave us chapsticks as souvenirs and guided us into the salt cave session. Here they give you a blanket and ask you to choose a seat for the meditation session. It is about 40 minutes of meditation which is supposed to help you unwind in a cave surrounded with salt that have anti-inflammatory effects. There were about 10 people in our session. They close the doors when the session starts and the voice overhead gives you an introduction of what we are about to experience. Unfortunately I didn't experience any of that. I did not experience and salt particles blown from the holes they pointed to. I did not see anything happening in the cave and felt no difference. About 15 minutes into the session one of the couple decided to leave, running across the cave to the exit. This disturbed everyone. Couple minutes later another couple left again making the exit known. 
Overall, 300$ was not worth this experience. Nothing met my expectations, I could have found more peace at a local spa. To begin, my massage was disrupted with loud plumbing problems, and second my cave session was disrupted with inconsiderate people leaving while the "mediation" was in session.

name: Kiwi's Auto Repair
attributes: {'ByAppointmentOnly': 'False', 'WiFi': "u'free'", 'BusinessAcceptsCreditCards': 'True'}
categories: Wheel & Rim Repair, Auto Customization, Transmission Repair, Auto Repair, Automotive, Oil Change Stations
text:
Had a really negative experience here last Friday and I'm shocked because I chose to go there based on all the great reviews. To preface this: I'm 9 months pregnant. My car wouldn't start outside the bank and after trying to have it jumped I called Kiwi's (based on the reviews) and the owner nicely said, sure, tow it on over and we'll look at it. The owner and a mechanic determined very quickly that it was the starter. After explaining to me the part would be $250 and labor $250, I texted my husband to let him know. My husband called to CarQuest and learned that the actual price for the exact part was $130. He came down to Kiwi's to discuss the price for the repair with the owner because it seems much too expensive. First of all he said he refused to put a cheaper starter in my car, then when my husband pressed him and said he had looked up the part and knew what the price was, then Rich changed his story and said that to stay in business he HAS to markup all his parts 100%. We said we would like to take the car somewhere else. Rich then threatened that "that's fine but I'll still charge you $120 for looking at it." So now feeling stuck and taken advantage of, we let him fix my car and paid him the $500. Meanwhile I got on Google and talked to another trusted mechanic and learned that the fair price of a starter repair on my vehicle in this zip code should be around $300 or at the very most $400. I still feel sick about it and cried at spending that much extra money unnecessarily at 9 months pregnant. 
I'm truly sorry if this man is having trouble staying in business for financial reasons but taking advantage of vulnerable pregnant women ISN'T the the way to make ends meet.

text:
Believe the hype. 

We were looking for a quick, casual place to eat some awesome food. With an almost 2 year old in-tow and a 3 hour drive to LA - time was of the essence. Los Agaves hit the spot in every way!

We stopped by on our way to LA for dinner. We were greeted warmly at the door with smiles and a menu. Be sure to double check the specials board above the cashiers! The girl who rang us up was also super friendly and helpful. The salsa bar is fantastic and the food came out within 10 minutes!

Poblano chilies were amazing and my husbands' fish tacos were excellent!

Another plus - Street parking was easy to find! We will definitely be back when we are in Santa Barbara!

categories: Event Planning & Services, Hotels, Hotels & Travel
text:
I booked three nights recently as a weekend getaway for a group of my friends.  The hotel itself was quite nice.  As a previous reviewer had noted, it does feel like an old building that's been spruced up.  The beds are comfy and the bathrooms are well done.

The two disappointments were more technological than the actual experience.  Their website had advertised flat screen TVs and high-speed Internet.  Our room had a 15 inch Zenith television that looked like it was from 1985, and the Internet would load pages at mind-numbingly slow speeds, often timing out altogether.  I called the front desk about my  connection issues, and the guy at the counter informed me that they were in the process of installing new routers.

Also, there isn't an in-house restaurant anymore.  The main image should probably be updated to something that isn't food.

Either way, it's a great location, decent pool facilities, and a comfy place to stay when exploring Santa Barbara.

categories: Local Services, Pest Control
text: We used Hydrex to inspect and repair termite damage on a home we were putting on the market. They mapped out needed repair areas, and quoted us about $1800 for repairs. After two days effort, they said the roof needed repair, and they could not complete their termite repairs until that was done. We agreed, and used Martin Roofing to replace the roof. Then we got the bill from Hydrex for their uncompleted repairs. Although they had completed less than 50% of the mapped out termite repairs (the original Hydrex mapped out repair areas did not include any of the roof repairs)  they sent a bill for $1700, or about 95% of the original estimated bid. We protested and after several email exchanges and threats by Hydrex to hold up our sale, we settled for $1200--fortunately, we photographed their work progress, and we could prove that Hydrex tried to cheat us by billing for work that was never done. We fired them and used Martin Roofing to complete the work--Martin did a great job and were honest throughout. I would not recommend using Hydrex for anything. They can't be trusted.

text: I went in to have the Photodynamic therapy/Blue light treatment for sun damage as suggested by my dermatologist (this is not done at my doctors office so I went to Dr. Gammon being that I used to see Dr. Brokken). I spoke w/ lady in office in detail more than once about the treatment and how it is done. She told me there is a certain lady that does this on Fridays. The whole thing was a horrible experience and a waist of time/money. First of all, There was no certain woman. The doctors assistant put the solution on my face and took me to a room down the hall to sit and wait.They did not leave the solution on for the full time I was told. They were not set up/prepared for my treatment. Dr. Gammon himself came to get me and put me under the light. He seemed rushed and nothing was set up. They LEFT ME ALONE during the whole time I was under the light and told me to yell for the woman (book keeper) down the hall if I needed anything. I did as the solution was running into my eyes. She did not even hear me calling her!! I noticed The light was filthy from previous treatment. Very frustrating and upsetting It did not do what I was told. Made No difference to my sun damage and I had to take two days off work to stay inside as I was told I must do after the treatment. I have filed a grievance w/ my insurance and now I have received a copy of the letter that the office has sent to my insurance and there are several topics they have stated in this letter that are not true. I am an honest, trusting business person and feel this whole thing is wrong and very unprofessional!!

categories: Restaurants, Sandwiches, American (New)
text:
Whenever we are in Santa Barbara we make sure to include a trip to Louie's.  Located in the Upham hotel, the space is quaint and cozy.  It reminds me of what it would be like to eat on grandma's wrap around porch in the south, but with elevated food and the best waiters in town.
This is was the first time we rolled the dice and took our children (7 and 3) and they could not have been more accommodating.  Our waiter was very knowledgeable on the wine list and even had a few other options not listed in the back.  They do not have a full bar but they make it up for it with a good wine selection.
We had the crab meat dumplings (good, the sauce is heavy cream so be warned), scottish salmon (one of my favorites, but again the sauce is a little heavy) and the filet - their filet is so freaking good and always cooked to perfection.  Kids were able to split pasta with butter and cheese and ate their weight in bread.  Thanks Louie's, we'll see you next time!

text:
Had dinner here for the first time the other day...here's the good & the not so good:

GOOD
-enchilada sauce
-black beans (soooo tasty)
-rice (moist & cooked perfectly)

NOT SO GOOD
-You have to *pay* for chips! WHAT?!?!?! I've never had to pay for chips in a Mexican restaurant before (booooo on them)
-lack of enchilada sauce: while it was delicious, they are REALLY SKIMPY on the sauce that my enchilada looked dry (why are you guys soooo cheap?!)

Would I go back? MAYBE. The food was good but having to pay for chips & being so skimpy on the portions left a bad taste in my mouth...

name: Camp Canine
attributes: {'BusinessAcceptsCreditCards': 'True', 'ByAppointmentOnly': 'False', 'RestaurantsDelivery': 'True'}
categories: Pet Sitting, Pets, Pet Training, Pet Boarding, Pet Services, Pet Groomers
text:
This place is the best resort/spa/training center in Santa Barbara.  The staff is friendly, the place is clean, and the campy atmosphere makes you feel like you are at a camp in the high sierras.  I have two dogs who love going there more than anything.  They all know my dogs and call them by name.  They always fit them in for a drop off day care, or bath even if it is last minute.  If I cannot pick them up their concierge service will drop them off at my front door.  Mary Sorosky the owner is the engine behind the place, she is always finding the most organic, newest nutritional dog food for your pet.  My dogs waste used to smell. She now has them on a food called NRG which when soaked in hot water and mixed with high quality kibble their waste no longer smells.   My 6-9 year olds are fitter than they have ever been and are never sick due to the excellent diet she has them on. She is more knowledgable about nutrition than a lot of vets in this town. They are currently putting in a therapy pool which older and arthritic dogs will enjoy.  No other dog spa can hold a candle to this place.  The other owner, John Sorosky brings over 25 years of experience training everything from puppies to difficult dogs.  Both of them rescue all types of dogs, rehabilitate them, and find them suitable homes.  I can honestly say my dogs love camp canine as much as being on the couch at home.  
I have heard that some competition moved a few blocks away, what competition?  They are the best at what they do, and with their 50 years of combined experience in the dog industry, no one can claim this in SB. They live, eat, breathe dogs.  Its not job for them its really a way of life.

text:
I've visited Jeannine's quite a few times for lunch and absolutely love everything I've ever tried! This most recent trip was a fun brunch with some girlfriends to the upper state location. 

With a large group of 7, I was expecting a long wait and a fight to get our own large table. But I was pleasantly surprised to see that the host now gets a table for you before you head to the counter to place your order! We waited less than 10 minutes for a table and less than FIVE minutes from when we ordered our food at the counter to receiving our food at our table!! 

We loved the little Jeannine's annex at the upper State location had plenty of room, indoors and outdoors for everyone. 

Everyone at the table enjoyed our meals of French toast, Benedicts, breakfast quesadillas, lattes and mochas. I especially loved my lobster Benedict and my iced Havana latte. This was definitely a fancy breakfast experience!

Other than the floral department, this is the most useless grocery store I have ever been to in my entire life. Bakery has the most unwilling staff that can't spellcheck (a time when it counts!). They also won't write on an instore, pre-made cake without numerous threats of messing it up if they attempt to. "We can but it won't look good." Then why are they there? 

Checkout in front was painful as usual in a college town employed mostly with insufferable and self-entitled staff. I get less attitude and more help at an Albertsons, which is embarrassing. I guess the service and level of competence in all the Wholefoods I have been to in LA and San Diego have spoiled me.

text:
This place is our staple breakfast location when visiting Santa Barbara and we will make a special trip down to Carp to come here.  This past weekend we came down SB to celebrate our friends engagement (congrats J & B!!), and knew we had to eat here for breakfast Sunday morning.  

All the food is fantastic and made with love by the owners.   If the excessive bee trinkets and garden soft colors start to make you nauseous just look at the food in front of you, all will be forgiven.  All your basic comfort breakfast foods are there and done well.  French toast, waffles, crispy thick cut bacon, fresh, perfectly scrambled (or basted if you're lucky) eggs and the list goes on.  The biscuits are by far the best I've ever had and if you've got room have them smother it in gravy.  You won't be disappointed.

categories: Asian Fusion, Poke, Seafood, Food, Restaurants
text:
This is flavorblast 3000. On variety alone, 10/10. If you're just passing through SB like myself, PokeCeviche is THE spot to guarantee a tasty, reasonably-priced meal.

Still open late, even during the pandemic. For COVID safety purposes, social distancing is enforced, hand sanitizer is provided, and patrons/staff must wear masks. Parking in this area is mostly street parking, but relatively easy to find.

The space is huge! And very clean. Coming into the shop at 10pm, it felt as though we were walking into a surgeon's room with how sterile, white, and quiet it was. Very much a refreshing change from how most poke places in the bay usually blast EDM.

CUSTOM POKE BOWL: This is just a wild medley of flavors and I'm all about it. Not a single thing in this bowl was bland. The brown rice/quinoa is great, but the jalapeño rice? AMAZING. Their fish is so fresh throughout the pokes and ceviches. Great spread of dry and wet toppings. And the sauces. Are. Flames. Get that citrus ponzu on top of the sriracha mayo, you won't regret it.

MISO SOUP: I cashed in on the check-in deal (free miso soup with every Yelp check-in!), and it was alright. The miso paste tends to run a little saltier (likely not diluted/mixed enough), but not the worst I've ever had. Besides, who's going to a poke spot for their miso anyway?

I might be living under a rock, but PokeCeviche is the only spot I've seen offer options this unique, from meal choices, to bases, to proteins, to toppings, to sauces-- every step of the way, there was something I'd never seen before. I'd recommend any poke connoisseur to try it out!

name: Father Jerry Bellamy
categories: Event Planning & Services, Officiants, Wedding Planning
text: Father Jeremy Bellamy is a warm and beautiful soul. Anyone lucky enough to have him preside over their nuptials will surely enjoy his humor and will be blessed immeasurably by the love he not only bestows unto their union, but the love that he promotes as the essential component in such a union. As a Wedding Photographer, I am privy to many beautiful wedding ceremonies; but none have produced such a profound and simple message as the message that Father Bellamy ushers into the world. Sure, most officiants talk of  the importance of love and commitment, and many incorporate scripture and/or some sort of religious framework as steadfast backing to why such commitments are important; but it is with Father Bellamy's officiating style that we are able to get a beautiful glimpse of God's sincerest intention for us, which is to be people who reside always in a place of LOVE. His message is universal, welcoming, lasting, and sincere. I cannot recommend him enough.

text: Came her the other day without a reservation. If you want to eat here make sure you have a reservation or show up before 9am.  Waiting only a few minutes was absolutely fine. Seated at a great table and ordered the endless scramble. My wife ordered the salmon and my step daughter ordered eggs as well. We ordered coffee and family mimosa as well as a pretzel.  The food was all prepared perfectly. Coffee was good and strong and the mimosa being described as serving 2-4 is inaccurate.  It could serve more....it's served 3 of us 2.5 servings......excellent with quality bubbles and fresh squeezed OJ.   You may wonder why four stars and not five.....I don't demand perfection and I'm not hard on restaurants in general. Only complaint was that we ordered the pretzel to arrive before brunch and the waiter forgot it.  Also mixing up the toasts isn't a big deal either but it happened.  It so happens whole wheat sourdough isn't bad....just not what I ordered. Our pretzel came out after reminding the waiter about it.  So, not perfect so not 5 stars. I will definitely recommend this to others for sure and I will go back again as the food is excellent and the outdoor atmosphere makes it the perfect (almost) Santa Barbara experience. The handmade toffee that came with the check was awesome and a neat treat as was the small sampling of yogurt, granola and dried cranberry that arrived at the table when we did.  It is a must to have brunch here.

text:
I was recently here on a weekend after a fabulous dim sum brunch. My family and I love to dine here for the very best dessert in town- the Swedish princess cake. To die for. 
Unfortunately our experience was thwarted by the service. We love to order a selection of dessert and preferably a bottle of rose champagne. The server poured a bottle of flat rose wine without informing us that they were out of the Rose bubbles. When we protested, the following bottle of champagne was served warm, no ice. No ice bucket. Honestly, it ruined the whole experience of splurging on an afternoon of fun with my family. My advice to management is: you have a beautiful cafe, delicious desserts, served on a fantastic street- invest in employee training. Elevate your service to match your delicious food.

text:
Only 2 people were working when we came.  One person taking the orders and only one preparing the food. 
They ran out of many things. I took the half BLT waffle sammie ($4.50 if I remember right), because I heard they kept telling people they ran out of chicken and a lot of other stuff. It wasn't even 1pm. 

We waited for more than 20 minutes, as they had informed us after the order. 

The waffle Sammie itself was good, but very greasy : my hands were wet because of the fat of the bacon which had not been taken off + the oil of the waffle. I also noticed it didn't have the caramelized. onions. They probably ran out of it, but didn't inform us. 

I think we might have fallen on a bad day, but I felt like the organization was amateurish. The waffle Sammie concept is tasty though. I just think it needs some improvement on the organizational side!

text:
Other reviewers here have covered the food portion pretty well, but I wanted to comment on the excellent service we received.  When we went, they had this 3 maitre-d set-up - one "standard" and two "floating"

Here's the set-up

- Friday before Memorial day
- 7:30 pm, no reservation
- Just pulled in from a couple days of hiking in the Central Coast (definitely not looking like the "typical" clientele)
- Place is packed

As we're checking out the menu, one of the guys comes out and asks if we have any questions.  Totally did not need to do that.

After we walk in, we're told that nothing is available at the moment, but if we want to come back in 10 minutes, they should have something

Coming back 10 min later, each of the 3 different guys approached us within a minute to ask if we were being helped and went to check on a table for us.

Words don't do justice to how efficient the attentive they were.  Wow, just set the tone for the rest of the meal.   If anybody from Opal is reading this, great job.

text:
They do tacos.  That is it.  They do them well.

These are real Mexican tacos: just little tortillas with meat.  No cheese and no beans.

The asada was really dry the night we went, but the pork and the steamed beef were good.

The salsa bar is darn good.

There was a line of thirty people, nearly all college students, out the door by the time we sat down.

name: Condor Express Whale Watching
attributes: {'BusinessAcceptsCreditCards': 'True', 'GoodForKids': 'True', 'BikeParking': 'True', 'BusinessParking': "{'garage': False, 'street': False, 'validated': False, 'lot': False, 'valet': False}"}
categories: Whale Watching Tours, Hotels & Travel, Event Planning & Services, Boating, Active Life, Tours, Boat Charters
text:
My boyfriend and I visited back in October 2020 for his birthday. What an amazing experience! I can not recommend this whale watching company enough. My boyfriend is a Marine Biology major, a scuba diver, and marine life lover. He was so impressed with how many whales and dolphins we saw on our trip. 

Condor Express is truly one of the best whale watching companies in Santa Barbara. They do their research on where to find the whales and we saw about 4-5 whales on our trip. However, I did get a little seasick. The ride was around 2 hours long and they did have food available. Since I'm not really that big of a fan of boats, I took a little nap because I felt super dizzy and seasick. I still enjoyed the trip and I'm glad my boyfriend had a great time. 

We got great photos and my boyfriend is longing to go back! Thank you Condor Express for such a great time and I'm sorry we were a little bit late when we arrived. You guys are awesome! We will definitely be back. If you're in Santa Barbara, give this place a try.

text: Maeda is amazing because it combines two great things: sushi and the term "all you can eat". Now usually when i see all you can eat sushi I run because it means crappy fish in tiny portions but that's not the case here. Now the portions are a little smaller than if you were to not get all you can eat but the important thing is the quality of the fish. They not only have great normal sushi but they also sometimes have local fish and more rare fish. If you go there and they have ono or local yellowtail don't hesitate to order it, its amazing.

text:
Love it!  Small intimate & warm place.  We had tasting menu with wine pairings (where they give you a choice of 3,5 or 7 courses, and you can choose from menu which options you want!).  I had 5 course -  with Foie Gras, Arugula salad, Rock Fish, Parpadalle with mushrooms and then Pork Belly.  Then had a bite of my friends grapefruit sorbet.  Everything was great.  My only comment is that the Pork Belly was a bit fatty (which is common with this cut), but still delicious!  Wine pairings were fantastic too, especially an unusual dry Riesling that was served with arugula salad.

A few things to note; wine only (no liquor bar) &  reservations needed although they appear to have 5 seats at bar that maybe used for last minute seating (all were full).

YUM, definitely will go back!

text:
Mahi Mahi Fish Tacos = Excellenté!!

So this is for my dumb-dumb file:  I didn't read the complete description of the salad I ordered.  When it arrived, I just couldn't eat it because it had ground walnuts that I passed off for bacon.  Yes, I'm a minority; I don't eat bacon.  When our server took it away, I privately pouted for about 20 seconds because the salad looked really good otherwise.  The Manager immediately came to our table and clarified that there was no bacon in the salad.  [Insert  dumb-dumb comment here].  She wanted to make something that I liked and offered to replace it - wow!  (Can I have the old salad back now and I'll shut up).

My husband had the Coq au Vin -- he was happy.   We were both happy -- but especially happy with their softball-sized chocolate mousse truffle!

Thank you for making our trip from the SF Bay Area really worthwhile!

They also had the perfect sofa at an unbelievable price.

When it was time for delivery, Mike called to see if we could move the time up from the original schedule.  I said I was going to the hardware store to get nuts & bolts for a table that came to me with the wrong parts.  Mike said, :"oh no, don't do that, I have those in my truck  I bet I have the right parts.".  And he did.  He gave me the parts and assembled the table!  Both those services are above and beyond the call of duty and very much appreciated.

I would not hesitate to send my friends here!

categories: Restaurants, Beauty & Spas, American (New), Event Planning & Services, Hotels, Massage, Resorts, Day Spas, Hotels & Travel, Venues & Event Spaces
text:
First the bad, so I can end on a some what positive note.  I stayed in a room which was spacious, but was next to the stairwell and at 6:30 in the morning it sounded like a heard of cattle walking up and down the stairs and the hallway.  Also my neighbor in the next room decided to move her chair out on the grass area where I could see her and loudly discuss with her other guests about how horrible her sister was.  Needless to say I did not come to a resort to have to listen to a loud mouth.  I decided to get a massage which was pricey at $180, but the massage therapist recommended a different massage since I had so many injuries.  I said sounds good.  She said the add on would be about $35 dollars.  Well the total was $258 dollars.  There is no massage in world worth that.  Next I noticed that in the welcome package I was supposed to have two complimentary bottles of water and a bottle of wine.  I called to the front desk this morning to explain, that there was no wine.  She said she would send someone down.  An hour later I called her to tell her I was going to check out and wanted to take the bottle with me.  She once again told me that she would send someone down.  No one came.  I went to the front desk to check out and she begrudgingly gave me the bottle.  I also mentioned the blinds in the room on two of the windows.  I asked her why they were see through.  Having flimsy blinds means the light comes through at 6:00 in the morning.  Between the heard of cattle walking up and down the stairs and the light coming through at 6:00 in the morning, I'm exhausted.  

The good.  I had a nice view of the ocean from my room and some really wonderful room service, although the menu was very limited.  When I asked for a small scoop of gelato room service told me they only sell it by the pint, but there ice cream fridge was broken so they didn't have any anyway.  

Not at all impressed.  I would not recommend this place to anyone!

categories: American (New), Food, Specialty Food, Restaurants
text:
Buddha Bowls is one of the last bastions of Isla Vistan cuisine, encompassing both drunchies and hangover food. Carb-laden goodness, fresh veggies, and massive bread bowls -- what's not to love?

In the nearly four years I've lived here, I've seen the prices here creep up steadily, to the point where a Mac Daddy bowl (bacon mac and cheese in a sourdough bread bowl for me) costs nearly $10. Bowls range between $7.50 and $10.

That being said, the big problem is that the line gets long as they prep bowls to order. Bread is sent through a continuous convection oven, butter-basted and broiled, there might be a pot of tomato basil bisque waiting to come to a broil, and there's never more than two or three people working on the assembly line, so it takes forever. I think I timed it last time I came to get some garlic bread and mac and cheese, and it took nearly 35 minutes.

If you want a healthy departure from bread but don't like the acai bowl trend, consider their melon bowl. It's a hollowed-out cantaloupe with yogurt and tons of fruit, including berries and melon. They also have salads, if that's your lunch of choice.

During my most recent visit, I've noticed that they've stepped it up and added some fresh drinks like lemonade, an agua fresca, and milk tea to their repertoire. Still not a bad place to visit for a tasty meal, but budget some time for your food to be made and to savor each bite of delicious bread.
